<head>
<title>Thompson's Philosophy</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Private School Choice: <br>
Governor Thompson's Philosophy </h2>
</center>
<hr>
<br> 
<h3><center>Improve Education </h3></center><p>
Milwaukee Public Schools are in dire straits.  Nearly half of its students 
don't graduate, and those who do graduate with an average of 1.6 grade 
point average, which breaks out to a D+. Therefore we need to try new 
ideas geared to breaking the status quo and improving education in 
Milwaukee, particularly for inner city students.  Keep in mind, the 
governor only sees School Choice as one element to the solution; there is 
no silver bullet for this problem. That is why it is imperative that new 
ideas and initiatives be given a chance in Milwaukee. We need to be 
innovative.  <p>
<center><h3>Parent Power </h3></center>
The governor believes that parents need to be empowered as an important 
first step in improving education. Getting parents more  
involved in choosing the school their child attends and monitoring how  
they are doing at that school is a gigantic plus toward making sure  
students are more dedicated to learning and getting a better education.  
The school choice program empowers parents -- particularly poor  
parents -- by giving them a choice. Right now, they don't have a choice.  
They're stuck with the public school the state says their child must  
attend. <p>
<center><h3>Opportunity/Equity </h3></center>
This is at the core of the governor's beliefs. He believes that poor parents 
in Milwaukee should have the same opportunities to educate their 
children as more wealthy parents. Right now, if a wealthy parent is 
unsatisfied with the child's public school, she can afford to send her to a 
private school of higher quality. She has a choice. A poor mother at the 
corner of Sixth and North in Milwaukee doesn't have a choice because 
she cannot afford to send her child to a private school. She's stuck. The 
governor believes that is unfair and detrimental to that child's education 
and future opportunities. The governor sees school choice as just one 
vehicle to provide more opportunities for poor children and families -- 
opportunities that will hopefully enable them to climb out of poverty and 
break the generational cycle. <p>
As a related issue, it's very interesting that a study by the Center for  
Education Reform showed that 33 percent of Milwaukee public school  
teachers send their own children to private schools. First, they can afford  
it and have a choice, unlike poor parents. Second, what's good enough  
for school teachers' kids should be good enough for poor kids. Yet, the  
teachers union is the biggest opponent of school choice. <p>
<center><h3>Constitutionality </center></h3>
If anything is inconsistent in the constitutional question it is that religious 
school choice is not allowed at the K-12 level. Currently, public money is 
allowed to be spent at private, religious pre-schools and day care centers 
(via day care grants) and at religious colleges and universities (via Pell 
grants, G.l. Bill, student loans.) It is only at the K-12 level that we say 
"no," public money can't be spent on private education. Why? School 
choice is very consistent with past practices in this country when it comes 
to education. Also, the voucher system helps address constitutionality 
questions. The parents control the voucher; they decide where it is spent. 
All we're saying is that if they want to spend that voucher at a religious 
school, that is allowable. <p>
<a href="welcome.html.cgi">Introduction</a>
</body>
</html> 
 
 

