<head>
<title>Religious School Choice Plan</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<i>June 29, 1995</i>
<hr>
<br>
<h2>Gov. Thompson's Religious School Choice Plan Passes</h2><p>
<i><b>Wisconsin becomes first state to offer real education choices to poor 
parents</b></i> 
</center>
<hr>
<br> 
MADISON -- Gov. Tommy G. Thompson's watershed religious school 
choice program was passed by the Wisconsin Legislature on Thursday, 
making Wisconsin the first state in the nation to give poor parents  
the full opportunity to choose where to send their children to school. <p>
The religious school choice program is limited to the city of Milwaukee, 
where the state's current non-sectarian school choice program is already 
in operation. In 1990, Wisconsin became the first state to pass private, 
non-sectarian school choice. <p> 
"The expansion of our school choice program to include religious schools 
will truly empower the poor parents of Milwaukee, giving them the same 
educational choices for their children as other parents," Gov. Thompson 
said. "If a poor inner city mother wants to send her child to the private 
school across the street, rather than busing her child across town to a 
public school she is dissatisfied with, she should have that opportunity 
regardless of her income." <p> 
"Religious values aren't our problem. Drop out rates and low test scores 
are," the governor added. "School choice is a belief that parents know 
best when it comes to their children, not bureaucrats." <p> 
The religious school choice program will accommodate 7,000 students 
beginning with this fall's school year, with an increase to 15,000 students 
in the 1996-97 school year and thereafter. <p> 
The state Legislative Fiscal Bureau estimates the program will cost $17 
million the first year and $39 million the second year for a total of $56 
million. The money will come from a reduction in state aid to Milwaukee 
Public Schools commensurate with the number of students participating 
in the choice program In other words, the money follows the child. The 
payment for each participating student would be equal to whichever is 
less: the private school's operating cost as determined by the state 
education department (on average about $2,800), or the states per pupil 
aid to MPS (about $4,000 in l995-96). <p> 
The religious school choice program gives vouchers to parents who then 
choose the school for their child, thus addressing any constitutionality 
concerns. The governor notes that the state and federal government  
currently pays for children to attend religious preschools or day care 
centers and for students to attend religious colleges and universities, so 
it's now time to include K-12 schools in the mix. <p> 
To be eligible for the program, a student must come from a family whose 
income- is at or below 175 percent of the poverty level (about $26,000 
for a family of four ) For schools to be eligible, they must be  
located within the city of Milwaukee.<p>   
Religious school choice was passed as part of Gov. Thompson's 1995-97 
biennial budget bill. The governor plans to sign the bill within the next 
month. <p>
<a href="welcome.html.cgi">Introduction</a>
</body>
</html>






