<h2><center>
	OUT OF THEIR OWN MOUTHS:<br>
	SELECTED QUOTATIONS ON THE<br>
	SIGNIFICANCE OF GOALS 2000</h2>
<b><hr size="3" width="30%"></center><br>
"The enactment of the Goals 2000: Educate America Act and the School-to-Work Opportunities Act signaled the beginning of a new era in education reform that <u>will over time touch all schools</u>."<br>    
	<i>--Department of Education Justifications of Appropriation Estimates to   	the Congress Fiscal Year 1996 Volume I</i><p><br><br>

America 2000, President Bush's educational reform plan, was the predecessor of Goals 2000.  "It was a self-proclaimed conservative Republican... who was advocating <u>a monumental movement away from local control of education</u>."<br>    
	<i>--John F. Jennings, Institute for Educational Leadership</i><p><br><br>

"When the legislative dust settles and future historians examine the Clinton Administration, they will devote a major chapter to the Goals 2000: Educate America Act.... Like President Lincoln's Morrill Act of 1862 and President Johnson's Elementary and Secondary Education Act of 1965, President Bill Clinton's Goals 2000 Act will stand as an education beacon."<br>     
	<i>--Richard W. Riley, U.S. Secretary of Education</i><p><br><br>

"[Goals 2000 is] the most important education legislation we've ever had." <br>   
	<i>--Albert Shanker, President, American Federation of Teachers</i><p><br><br>

"In the first three titles, Goals 2000 establishes overall direction for a new local-state-federal partnership in education." <br>   
	<i>--Gordon M. Ambach, Executive Director, Council of Chief State School 	  Officers</i><p><br><br>

"Perhaps most important, Goals 2000 lays the conceptual groundwork for other federal legislation, establishing a model for coherence among federal and 
national endeavors in education that has never been seen before...." <br>   
	<i>--Jennifer O'Day, Associate Director, Pew Forum on Education Reform </i><p><br><br>


"Goals 2000 is a new way of doing business in America.  It represents the direction our government must take in many problems in the 21st century."  <br>  
	<i>--President Bill Clinton </i></b><p><br><br>

