<html>
<head>
<title>Ed Facts</title>
</head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center><h2>A Back-to-School Primer</h2>August 11, 1995<p><a name="contents">Contents</a><br><a href="#issues">Important Issues</a><br>
<a href="#disappoint">Disappointments and Dissenters</a><p><hr size =3 width=30%></center><br><p>
<a name="issues"><h3>Important education issues to expect during the fall session of the 104th Congress</h3></a><br><a href="#contents">[Contents]</a><br>
<h4>ACTION:  Set up an appointment to meet with your Congressman or Senator at their district offices during the August recess, which lasts from now until Labor Day. Use this outline of issues for your meeting:</h4>


<b>I.  Ending federal programs for America's schools</b>. Of the 552 education programs the federal government runs at a cost of $70 billion (244 in the Education Department, 308 in 30 other agencies), it's difficult to point to many that have been successful, let alone cost-effective. It's time to question the federal role in education, and two bills are doing just that:<p>   
<ul>
<li>The Back to Basics bill (H.R. 1883) goes after most of the programs in the U.S. Education Department, consolidates them into a block grant to be administered by the Department of Health and Human Services and moves remaining programs to other departments.<p>

<li>The Restoring Local Schools bill goes further.  Developed by conservatives, this bill would immediately eliminate the U.S. Education Department and repeal many of the 552 federal education programs.  Three block grants, to end within four years, would replace them.  The highlight of this bill is its provision for enactment of a tax cut to replace $60 billion in federal education spending. <p></ul>

<b>II.  Resist the Urge to Merge</b>.  Merging the U.S. Education and Labor Departments will not solve the problems created by the federal role in schools.  Equally objectionable is any merging of programs which might lead to a philosophy that does not differentiate between education and workforce preparation.  Two plans are moving in that direction:<p>
</ul>
<li>Congressmen Bill Goodling (R-Penn.) and Steve Gunderson (R-Wis.) have developed a plan to merge the U.S. Education and Labor Departments and fold in the EEOC as well.  They have determined that the federal government's legitimate role in education is workforce preparation, so that the country may benefit economically.  On that basis they would relocate the Education Department, reorganized but not reduced in size, in the Labor Department.  By maintaining the federal education bureaucracy and its current status as director of education in America, yet prioritizing its functions in such a way as to benefit labor, this plan sends a dangerous message that education is merely economic development.<p></ul>
									<h4>August 11, 1995</h4><br>
<ul><li>The CAREERS bill (H.R. 1617) is the first step toward the Goodling-Gunderson plan.  It would combine 90 job training programs into four block grants, but retain many School-to-Work ideas, including government-endorsed skill standards and skill certificates and career counseling for elementary students.  In addition, it creates an unneeded and wasteful "workforce development infrastructure," which would include creation of one-stop career centers.<p>
</ul>
<b>III.  Defund and Repeal Goals 2000</b>.  America has seen a new height in federal directives in education since the passage of Goals 2000 during the spring of 1994.  While rhetoric touts this program as voluntary, upon entry into the Goals 2000 contract a state will be compelled to follow the federal prescription for school restructuring:  development of standards and aligned assessments and submission of state plans to the U.S. Secretary of Education.  Efforts to end this inappropriate federal program are meeting with some success:<p>
<ul>
<li>The Labor/HHS/Education Appropriations Bill (H.R. 2127) passed the House late last week without funding for Goals 2000.  This bill also makes several important strides to reduce abortion.  The bill will go through the gauntlet of debate and mark-up on the Senate side when Congress reconvenes in September, beginning with the Appropriations Subcommittee on Labor/HHS/Education, then the full Appropriations Committee, and finally, the full Senate.  Subcommittee Chairman Sen. Arlen Specter (R-Penn.) has vowed his intention to reverse the victories that pro-family Americans achieved in this bill.  <p>

<li>Rep. John Shadegg (R-Ariz.) has been a leader in the charge against Goals 2000 on the House side. Earlier this summer he drummed up support for the elimination of Goals 2000 funding in the appropriations bill and also expressed his desire to see the program repealed.  <p></ul>

<a name="disappoint"><h3>DISAPPOINTMENTS AND DISSENTERS:  104TH CONGRESS ON EDUCATION</h3></a><a href="#contents">[ Contents ]</a><br><br>
	Conservatives have reason to be dismayed with the "Republican Revolution" which has little influenced the education theory coming out of this Congress.  A prime example is the Education Reform Consolidation Grant, which would combine over 50 elementary and secondary education programs into a single block grant, presumably in an attempt to reduce the federal role in education.  In current draft form, however, the bill maintains a Washington-knows-best philosophy by following the pattern of Goals 2000, including prescriptions for states to submit standards and assessments to the National Education Goals Panel, which would report to the U.S. Secretary of Education.  The education bureaucracy would be largely untouched by this supposed improvement.  <p>
	While most conservatives find the efforts of this Congress lacking when it comes to education, a few notable education theorists say the opposite.  Chester Finn of the Hudson Institute and Diane Ravitch of the Brookings Institution charge that "Republican anti-governmentalism occasionally becomes overwrought," referring to the effort to end the federal role in education.   In a report entitled "Education Reform 1994-95," they praise "reinvention" strategies like school choice and charter schools, yet cling to the status quo--federal oversight of America's schools.  Finn and Ravitch also support national standards and assessments. Unfortunately, standards and assessments will not directly improve student achievement; they will simply make it easier to evaluate and compare schools, thus empowering the beureaucrats that control the system.<p>								
[ <a href="welcome.html.cgi">Introduction</a> ]<br>
[ <a href="http://www.townhall.com/townhall/FRC/welcome.html>Family Reseach Council</a> ]
</body>
