<title>Education</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Education: A Plan for the Next Generation</h2><br>
<i><b>Robert L. Montgomerie </b></i>
</center>
<hr>
<br>
There is the large debate within the right concerning education. Much 
of the focus is the funding of education and the result we're getting 
from the sea of dollars that is spent on it. Much of the main focus is 
on the lack of certain skills on the part of youngster as opposed to 
older generations who seemed to have gotten a far more superior 
education then present generations. Quite a bit of anger is directed 
towards liberal policy with respect to the social part of education 
while many of the actually grade figures are more or less used in a 
rather curious way to justify the need for social reform in public 
education. Many of these arguments include the once practiced early 
morning prayer by students in the morning. Also it includes such 
things as an end to handing out condoms, an end to education regarding 
alternative lifestyles, and another broad practice that doesn't 
necessarily include alternative lifestyles but should is 
multiculturalism. Many camps within the right competing for jobs in 
the next two or three elections will be faced with these issues 
perhaps much more seriously in the future. Nativists who are a curious 
breed of quasi-conservatives are latching on to the ideas of changing 
the face of public school as we know it. Perhaps it should be changed. 
The only thing about education that will change will probably be a 
shift in liberal to conservatives policy regarding education to fit a 
more explicitly moral overtone linked to Christianity.<p>  
Much of the proposed reform that was been thrown around is the 
standard approach to cultural literacy that is proposed by many 
nativists calling for an end to revisionist history being taught 
currently. Many do not like the idea of Columbus being depicted as 
anything other than a visionary, or a Lincoln who personally didn't 
think blacks should hold elective office but it all boils down to a 
point of that they dislike the current thought in place of teaching 
other histories not pertaining entirely to the founding of the nation 
as we know it or of the origins of that nation. Much of this is linked 
to nationalist thought and it is linked to an idea of America as a 
Christian nation. It is known that America was here long before 
Europeans came just as it is known that George Washington's cherry 
tree story is not a very truthful story. Those of us who grew up with 
ideas of a Benjamin Franklin working hard are very astonished to find 
out that he had a very unpuritian stay in France and was a little bit 
of a ladies man while he was there. When faced with ideas of slave 
holding founding fathers would considered blacks and Indians as lesser 
men than them and even went so far as to write that into the 
Constitution as opposed to the idealized view of moral founding 
fathers who were straight edged to the end is a hard thing to take in. 
Especially when it may be true. <p>
The original purpose of public education was to create citizens who 
could speak a common language necessary for the smooth operation of a 
nation entering into the industrial revolution, have a literate 
population, and to instill the meaning of America and to explain the 
civil duties and benefits of being a citizen. Noble enough until you 
enter the agent of politics which of course seems to run any good idea 
into the rocks when given what seems to be a simple task. Funding 
education was simple also in the pre-industrial era and even into 
modern times so what went wrong when SAT scores have fallen 
consistently since 1960? Are schools adequate enough to teach students 
in these times? Is it a lack of work ethic among teachers to teach 
students in the classroom sitting? Is it a lack on the behalf of 
parents to teach children the importance of education which may 
include helping with homework or among other things personally 
insuring that children even participate in what many children in other 
country's don't get; a free education. <p>
In 1996 the Republican Party committed to social issues has to address 
the issue of education with a plan that takes necessary strains off of 
the budget plus aid in improving the quality of not only education but 
of schools and the institutions that run them. It would be easy to 
make this an ugly political background but it is hoped that out of a 
sense of decency that in front of young eyes there will be serious 
debate and little rhetoric bouncing. The Republican Party has to 
address ambitiously the issue of crime in schools all across the 
board, teaching, institutional social policy, curriculum, and cost and 
that isn't an easy job when so much special interest is at stake. The 
changes made in public education will affect a whole generation of 
young minds needed to shape a nation of the future and hopefully the 
reform of today will aid in this process and not in effect some to an 
institutional "rubber check" to show the true ineffectiveness of this 
generation in handling the challenges of today. <p>
Many of the contemporary ideas include such things as vouchers and 
reassigning responsibilities, including funding, to the states. Much 
of the idea concerning empowerment of the states fully in the 
education process as a statement in itself is a reasonable idea. One 
because states have a better idea of the field of endeavor children 
was go on such as banking, farming, and roping horses. States also 
have a better idea of  what children, residing in that state, need to 
work on and can create a better, more personalized plan to better 
attack these weaknesses and hopefully show an improvement in that 
general area. Conversely will states be able to cover the cost the 
federal government spends on education. In fiscal 1992 the federal 
government spent 26.04 billion for education. Will states be able to 
supply the needed resources to properly educate every child in every 
setting without federal help. Perhaps if states intend on opening more 
magnet type schools and even then access would still be limited. 
Lastly will states act with integrity in the social education of 
children. If the Federal Government leaves any indication then it is 
reasonable to expect that state governments will conduct themselves 
similarly. This is not to say that the states might not do a better 
job with education because of the fact that they haven't been given a 
chance. But nevertheless tax burden for education won't be taken off 
the backs of the taxpayer and there is reason to suspect that this tax 
burden will increase. Best case scenario will be that it won't change. 
It will just be collected by a different source. <p>
Should the federal government get out of the business of education? 
The answer is that the federal government should provide a leadership 
role in education, but the federal government should not be so 
financially committed to education as it has been in the past ten to 
twenty years. Realistically we can expect that the federal government 
won't be out of the education business within the next twenty years 
and this is where now the Republican Party can take a crucial role in 
molding the face of education of years to come.  <p>
One of the main objectives of the Republican Party is tax relief. Part 
of that is in ensuring that as much of a standard of equality exists 
in funding as well as in collecting funds. <p>
It should be considered unconstitutional to collect property taxes 
from all property owners in order to fund education. Many people who 
are paying for education don't even have children attending public 
school or don't have children at all or anymore. Why should they pay? 
Empowerment has to fit into the framework somewhere with regard to 
funding. As long as we know that it is here and that someone has to 
pay why can't those who participate pay for the system? Those who pick 
up the tab for public school should also have a larger say in what 
goes on in that which they are a partner of therein. Many in public 
life are clamoring for "vouchers" that will give families the right to 
take their children to any school they wish to attend. A voucher 
system is in itself an interesting idea; families taking their 
children to any school they wish and using this voucher to pay for it. 
How will this change the face of funding education? It won't. Vouchers 
are simply another form of government handout like free lunch tickets. 
There are three things that are a problem in public school that won't 
be cured by vouchers and one is overcrowded classrooms. In the 
meanwhile perfectly good schools will sit largely dormant and will be 
too expensive to run after a time mainly because of low attendance. 
Vouchers will also affect private school education with this same 
overcrowded problem the public schools are having. Currently 
classrooms are comprised of one teacher attempting to teach thirty or 
more students. Vouchers will only aid in this madness.  <p>
Since segregation many schools have been closed in order to achieve 
racial balance in communities especially in the south. That is very 
present in large cities where it isn't uncommon to find old school 
buildings dotting neighborhoods. Perhaps  federal money should be 
spent to reopen some of these buildings rather than that money being 
spent on chasing suburbanites into the countryside in order to insure 
the schools they open will meet a standard of equality. Opening 
schools will spread out the population and thus spread out the 
classrooms and those attending those classrooms. More schools would 
mean more funding to run these schools. If  it is already expensive to 
pay for the schools that exist then why expand on that problem. 
Simple. We know some reasons why there are the problems within many 
public schools. They are packed into classrooms, and hallways, and 
cafeterias like sardines. Teachers are expected to successfully teach 
roughly a classroom of thirty or more students so it is wise to note 
that not every student is getting the proper attention that student 
deserves. Are we interested in coming to at least as close of a 
solution as possible? If we are then we have to address the 
fundamental problems that currently exist. <p>
The important issue with respect to the last paragraph is in funding. 
We know that as fiscal conservatives we are committed to freeing up 
incomes. We are also committed to finding an equitable fair system of 
funding that will be efficient and as self sustaining as possible 
which is no easy task. Adding other principles such as personable 
responsibility and empowerment we can come to a partial solution of 
funding public education while achieving all goals. That partial 
solution would be The Public School Funding Act. This would create a 
middle ground to both tax relief, empowerment, personal 
responsibility, and improvement of institution. Part of the PSFA would 
include cutting property taxes used to fund education by half in order 
to ensure fairness in taxation and to also remove "penalties" on 
owning property. It would include cuts in the Department of Education 
budget on a graduated basis for five years by three million a year so 
that states will have ample time to absorb new budgetary demands. 
After the five year period the Department of Education would then 
operate at roughly half  of it present cost in fiscal 1996 and would 
retain a  cap on it's budget not to exceed  60% of the fiscal 1996 
budget. Funding will be used solely as aid to build schools, refurbish 
closed schools, and to provide grants as budgetary restraints allow. 
It will also require a user fee to be imposed on families who 
participate public schools with regards to income, cost of living 
within a particular area, and amount of children within that family 
who attend public school. This fee will be payable by the beginning of 
the next school year and that fee will be payable pass or fail. If 
they cannot afford the fee then arrangements will be made for their 
child to attend while they pay the fee. The PSFA will also call for an 
end of Magnet Schools as they will not be needed. States will be able 
to hold lotteries to fund education and will be required to relinquish 
all proceeds for that purpose if it is originally intended for that 
purpose. The PSFA will also allow neighborhood schools to solicit 
private business for contributions of funds and equipment such as 
computers, and any other items suitable for either liberal arts 
education or vocational education. This plan will ensure that fairness 
in funding public school will be paramount and that no one group will 
carry the entire burden.  <p>
The major objective of the PSFA is to return to  a more communities 
based education by diminishing the demand on few schools that exist in 
many cities. Families will have schools that they can be proud of and 
they will have schools that they will feel obligated to take an active 
interest in because they are a partner of that school. Also as 
partners who directly pay into their neighborhood school they will 
hopefully take a more active interest in their child's education and 
will hopefully take an active leadership role in insuring the success 
of their child in his academic endeavors. <p>
The need for an end to social experimentation in public schools is 
very relevant because it does not encourage children to be 
individuals. It is no more right to use schools for indoctrination 
purposes than it is to segregate them and make them exclusionary if 
they are provided by government at any level. Individuals come into 
agreement to form governments for the common good of those who choose 
live within that government therein. So to insure that the civil 
liberties of all students who attend public school won't be abridged 
within reason there is a need for an Ethics in Public School Act. This 
act would allow religious expression in public school. It would allow 
for groups who share a common religious bond to assemble for religious 
activities. The limits on these activities would be decided by local 
and state administrations. It will also protect any philosophical 
expression, speech, and belief as supported by the first amendment of 
the constitution. Anti-Discriminatory policies still apply. It will 
not provide for lead prayer in classrooms but it will not discourage 
any expression in private during a moment of silence. The EPSA would 
also make students who engage in a Felony such as murder, attempted 
murder, or dealing drugs within public school property will be 
punished as a mature adult. <p>
It is important for children and families to believe in the schools 
they are directly or indirectly taking a part in. It is also important 
for children not only to know that their civil liberties won't be 
abridged beyond absurdity, but it is important of all to know that 
they are individuals and that they live in a society of individuals. 
Part of knowing that is in being able to see the differences people 
possess. To know that all beliefs are supported will insure that 
mutual respect exist among students as long as they are in public 
school. <p>
These are ideas that the Republican Party should consider advocating 
in the up and coming election in 1996. They are fair and they would be 
simple to implement. As Republicans we can all agree it should be our 
purpose to limit government as much as possible while trying to be as 
fair as possible at the same time. We should also not be fearful of 
experimentation especially when the future of our children is at 
stake. <p>
<a href="welcome.html.cgi">Introduction</a>
</body>
</html>

