<html>
<head>
<title>VIOLENCE IN THE 
	SCHOOLHOUSE:</title>	
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center><h2>VIOLENCE IN THE<br> 
	SCHOOLHOUSE:<br>
	A 10-YEAR UPDATE</h2>
	<h4><i>by</i><br>
	<i>Robert L. Maginnis</i></h4></center
<center><hr size="3" width="30%"><br></center>
<h3><center><a name="contents">Table of Contents</a></h3></center><br>
<a href="#trend">School Violence Trend</a><br>
<a href="#impact">Impact of Violence in the Classroom</a><br>
<a href="#nature">Nature of School Violence</a><br>
<a href="#frequency">Types and Frequency of Violent Incidents</a><br>
<a href="#victims">Who are the Victims and Offenders?</a><br>
<a href="#where">Where Does School Violence Take Place?</a><br>
<a href="#what">What Is Being Done To Curb The Violence?</a><br>
<a href="#root">The Root Of School Violence</a><br>
<a href="#conclusion">Conclusion</a><br><br>
<hr><br>
In 1984, the Under Secretary of Education, Gary Bauer, released a report, Disorder in Our Public Schools, which highlighted the problem of school discipline with these startling facts:<br>
<ul>
<li>Teachers spent 30 to 80 percent of their time on discipline. <p>
<li>Half of all teachers felt misbehavior interfered with teaching to a "moderate or greater extent."<p>
<li>Three million high school students were victims of in-school crimes each month.<p>
<li>Eight percent of high school students missed at least one day each month because they were afraid of violence.<p>
<li>Four out of every 10 high school students had been a crime victim the previous year.<p>
<li>Each month 1,000 teachers re
Required medical attention because of in-school assaults 
and 125,000 were threatened.</ul><p>

Today, ten years after the Bauer report, the problems are worse.  America's schools are battlegrounds where children are too often physically harmed and deprived of a good education.  Teachers are more at risk than ever before.  Consider some recent examples of school violence.

<ul>
<li>A St. Louis student, 14, was stabbed at school.<p>
<li>An Atlanta student, 12, was shot at school by a friend showing off a stolen gun.<p>
<li>A 5-year-old and two 7-year-olds were suspended from school in Rockville, Maryland for bringing knives to school.<p>
<li>A 15-year-old fatally shot a schoolmate in a Los Angeles school.<p>
<li>A 14-year-old seventh grader was arrested in Wichita, Kansas after a pistol was found in his school locker.<p>
<li>Two Denver, Colorado high school students detonated a pipe bomb outside their school.<p>
<li>A New York City student was shot during a school basketball game.<p>
<li>The 1994 National Teacher of the Year helped her California students hide weapons "so they won't get killed after school."<p>
<li> A Maryland teacher caught a student with a pistol inside a school restroom.  The student shot the teacher.<p>
<li>A Dartmouth, Massachusetts high school student was knifed and clubbed to death during a government class.<p>
<li> An Atlanta student opened fire in a crowded school cafeteria, killing one student and wounding another.<p>
</ul>Violence at school is worse today than ten years ago.  The growing epidemic of school violence frightens children and their parents, undermines the education process, and threatens the future competitiveness of this country.  <p>

The school violence epidemic is rooted in larger societal problems.  Consider the current school violence trend, its impact on the education environment, an analysis of the changed nature of school violence, and the roots of the problem.<p>

<h3><center><a name="trend">SCHOOL VIOLENCE TREND</a></center></h3>

Michael Resnick, spokesman for the National School Boards Association (NSBA) states, "Just as the incidences of violence are increasing, so is the severity of the violence, so that this is becoming a much more serious problem in terms of numbers, location, and severity."<p>
School Superintendent Octavio Vistedof for Dade County, Florida, states, "There are children that witness more violence on their way to school on any given day than we as adults have witnessed in a lifetime, and yet we expect that child to come in and be, you know, summa cum laude and basically go in and graduate with honors.  It doesn't work that way."<p>
An NSBA survey shows that violence has increased each year over the last five years in 82 percent of the nation's school systems.<p>
The growing problem is especially felt by students.  The Institute for Social Research reports that 91.6 percent of high school seniors worry about crime and violence, and their greatest concern is drug abuse (77.8 percent).  Black female students from the South are the most likely to be worried.<p>
The indicators of school violence are everywhere.  For example, a recent Gallup poll found that in the past year one teen in five had a friend who was attacked by someone who was wielding a knife or gun, seven percent had been assaulted, 14 percent had their property vandalized, and 24 percent lived in a state of fear at school.<p>
Nearly 135,000 guns are brought into schools every day.19  About three million crimes occur on or near school property each year.20  Nearly a fifth of schools report student-on-teacher assaults.  And illegal drugs are available in at least 70 percent of our schools.<p>
The rising incidences of school violence also affect student views about law enforcement.  For example, at the time of Mr. Bauer's report, 36.9 percent of high school seniors had a positive attitude toward the performance of local police, but in 1992 confidence had declined to 26.9 percent.  It is especially low (12.4 percent) among black students.<p>
<center><h3><a name="impact">IMPACT OF VIOLENCE IN THE CLASSROOM</a></h3></center>
The 1984 Bauer report linked effective learning with a disciplined school environment.  Metropolitan Life Chairman Harry P. Kamen announced a recent nationwide public education survey which said that violence is so roiling the waters of public education that students cannot learn and teachers cannot teach.<p>
Kenneth Trump, coordinator of the Youth Gang Unit for the Cleveland Public Schools, states: "Besides the obvious physical harm caused by assaults and fights, the psychological impact to both staff and students can be damaging.  Students who are victims of school crimes or who perceive the school environment to be unsafe may not attend regularly and may not adequately concentrate on classwork when they do attend."  The National Education Goals Report found that in 1992 seven percent of 8th graders reported staying home from school at least once during the previous month because of concerns for their physical safety.<p>
Moreover, "teachers are not able to focus their efforts on instruction if they are preoccupied with disruptions and altercations.  Additionally, prolonged work in such environments is likely to increase teacher stress and reduce their overall classroom effectiveness."  The National Education Goals report shows that teachers were more often subject to physical and verbal abuse and in cities they tend to feel unsafe in their buildings after school hours.<p>
American Federation of Teachers President Albert Shanker explains, "The thread that ties this mixed bag of findings together is that, across the board, real or feared violence and a quality education are recognized as incompatible.  Schools have a primary mission -- to provide high standards, a challenging academic experience and maximum achievement for all students, but it won't work when the specter of violence is afoot.  The daunting effort to improve academic achievement is undermined every time a teacher is confronted by threatened or perpetrated trauma in the classroom or on school grounds, every time a student is afraid to go to school, and every time a parent neglects to set a good example at home."<p>
<h3><a name="nature">NATURE OF SCHOOL VIOLENCE</a></h3>
Dissecting school violence requires an examination of the types and frequency of violent incidents, a profile of the victims and offenders, and a profile of the crime sites.  

<h4><a name="frequency">TYPES AND FREQUENCY OF VIOLENT INCIDENTS</a></h4>

The Justice Department found that two percent of students reported experiencing one or more violent crimes and seven percent reported at least one property crime during the first half of 1989.29  The most common types of violence involved were simple assaults: pushing, shoving, grabbing, and slapping.  But more students than ever before brought weapons, including guns, to school.<p>

A Louis Harris poll found that 19 percent of central city schoolchildren report having had a physical fight in the past year and nine percent of suburban children have been suspended for the same reason.  A parallel finding shows that 32 percent of central city students have been physically threatened in the past month, compared to 29 percent in the suburbs.<p>
There are an estimated 71 weapon-carrying incidents per 100 students per month.  Typically boys carry weapons four times more often than girls, and the incidents are more common among Hispanic boys.  The weapon of choice is a knife or razor (55.2%) with the second choice being a club (24%).<p>
The National Education Goals Report found that in 1992 nine percent of 8th graders, 10 percent of 10th graders, and six percent of 12th graders reported they had brought a weapon to school at least once during the previous month.  A significant percentage frequently carried weapons to school.<p>
A Gallup poll found that weapon-toting students tend to use their weapons to settle disputes.  Twenty-one percent of students said they had been attacked with a knife or gun and, overall, assaults were reported by 63 percent of students. The poll found that nine percent of the students labeled weapons at school as a "very big problem."<p>
Guns at school are a special problem given their lethality.  A 1993 Louis Harris poll found that 11 percent of schoolchildren had been shot at by a gun in the past year, and 39 percent know someone personally who has either been killed or injured from gunfire.  Children enrolled in private and parochial schools "say they know how to get a gun than do those who go to public schools." <p>
A Justice Department report found that one in five suburban high school boys owns a gun, and that 45 percent of these boys have been threatened with a gun or shot at on the way to or from school during the previous few years.  Half of these boys said that they have friends who routinely carry a gun. <p>
<h4><a name="victims">WHO ARE THE VICTIMS AND OFFENDERS?</a></h4>
A 1993 Metropolitan Life survey, "Violence in America's Public Schools," found that 23 percent of students and 11 percent of teachers have been victims of violence in and around school.  MetLife reports that boys are twice as likely (30%) as girls (16%) to be victims of violence.<p>
The Justice Department found that public school students (9%) are more likely to be crime victims than private school students (7%).  Black and Hispanic students are more likely than white students to be victims of violent acts at school involving weapons.  Age, family income, and frequency of family moves were predictors of victimization: younger kids were more likely to be victims; students from homes with annual incomes of $50,000 or more were likely to be victims; and students from families that had moved three or more times in the last five years were crime victims twice as often as students who had not moved.<p>
Without factoring in age, family income and frequency of moves, teenagers from single-parent families are more likely to be violent crime victims than teens from two-parent intact families.  The statistics are the same whether the single parent is a mother or father.<p>
Fear of victimization varies by school location, type of school, and mode of transport to school.  For example, public school students (22%) are more likely than private school students (13%) to be fearful of attack at school.  Public school students are twice as likely as private school students to avoid certain areas at school.  And students who travel to school by car are the least likely to fear attack.<p>

Wesley Mitchell, commander of the Los Angeles Unified School District police, said, "Schools are feeling the outgrowth and the experiences of the larger community." This is especially true with regards to the violent student offenders.  Children bring to school the problems they have at home and in the community.<p>
A Washington State survey found that the more a student uses alcohol and other drugs or reports a history of physical or sexual abuse, the more likely he is to carry a weapon to school or to have been in a fight in the past year that resulted in injuries which required medical attention.  Boys (32%) are far more likely than girls (15%) to carry a weapon to school.  Hispanic (41.1%) and black (39.4%) male students are more likely to carry a weapon than white (28.6%) male students.<p>
Gangs promote violence in schools and, according to the Justice Department, 15 percent of schools have violence-prone gangs and 12 percent said gang members fought once or twice a week or even every day.  Students in central cities are more likely to report gangs at their schools (25%) than suburban students (8%), and black and Hispanic students (20% and 32%) say their schools have gangs more often than white (20%) students.Most (78%) students from schools with gangs report that a student can obtain drugs at school compared to 66 percent of students in schools without gangs.<p>
<h4><a name="where">WHERE DOES SCHOOL VIOLENCE TAKE PLACE?</a></h4>

The Justice Department explains in "Teenage Victims" that the likelihood of becoming a crime victim in a particular location is influenced by the amount of time spent in one location relative to another.  That's why schools, according to the Justice Department, are prime locations for teen crime.<p>
Teachers say that most acts of student violence take place in or around school.  Students are, however, less certain.  Police officials say that student violence is equally evident inside, outside, and in the school neighborhood.<p>
Teachers told Louis Harris that 64 percent of in-school violence takes place in the hallways or stairways, 16 percent in lunchrooms, 12 percent in the classrooms, and 15 percent in bathrooms.  Students believe more violence takes place in the classroom and athletic areas than teachers report.<p>
The Justice Department reports that six percent of students avoid some place in or around their school because of the potential that someone might attack them.  School restrooms were listed most often as a place to avoid and hallways were second. More than two-thirds of students don't feel completely safe going to and from school.
<h3><center><a name="what">WHAT IS BEING DONE TO CURB THE VIOLENCE?</a></h3></center>
School authorities are trying virtually anything that might curb the violence.  There are programs to help parents to reduce family violence.  There are groups who seek to reduce violence in television and music lyrics.<p>
<ul>
<li> NSBA surveyed school districts to determine the most common anti-violence strategies.  It found that suspension is used 78 percent of the time.  Other strategies include: expulsion (72%), locker searches (50%), security personnel in schools (36%), gun-free school zones (31%), metal detectors (15%), dress code (41%), and volunteer parent patrols (13%).<p>
<li> Orange County, Florida started a program that includes conflict resolution, peer mediation, and support groups. The S.A.F.E. program (Student Assistance and Family Empowerment) includes five students from each grade who are trained to offer mediation for students in conflict.<p>
<li> New York City public schools have S.T.A.R. (Straight Talk About Risks) which is designed to help students avoid crime.  The program teaches protective skills needed to avoid threatening situations with guns.<p>
<li> A Dayton, Ohio, program promotes character education, inculcating values like honesty, responsibility, courage, and loyalty.<p>
<li> Duval County, Florida uses local policemen to patrol schools and Denver, Colorado, has a special school security force.  A school in Tucson, Arizona built an eight-foot fence around the parking lot in response to a drive-by shooting.  In San Diego, California, schools recently removed all lockers to reduce hiding places for contraband.<p>
While some schools are on the offensive, trying to stem classroom violence, a recent Department of Justice study found that some of these anti-crime efforts don't make a significant difference.  For example, schools using hall monitors or patrols suffered the same incidence of violence as schools which didn't have these programs.  And students in schools with these programs were more likely to fear an attack than those attending schools without monitors and patrols.<p>
Even more troubling, an American Association of School Administrators report finds that some schools consciously and actively play down the incidence of violence.  This is done to avoid bad publicity, to avoid litigation, out of fear they will be regarded as ineffective, and to avoid being labeled as poor leaders.  Teachers under-reported crime and violence because they wanted to avoid litigation, had difficulty identifying the offender, and did not wish to stigmatize young offenders.<p>
The National School Safety Center recommends an action plan to achieve safe schools.  The plan includes:  assigning responsibility for developing a plan; consulting an attorney who knows education law, analyzing the nature and scope of the problem, identifying and implementing measures to fight the problem, establishing procedures for school employees, conducting regular in-service training for staff on school crime and violence, establishing procedures for students and parents to make suggestions, developing an effective relationship with local law enforcement and court officials, sharing information with other schools, and regularly evaluating programs.<p>
In spite of considerable expenditure of money and effort to curb the epidemic of school violence, no school district has yet declared victory.<p>
Parents are looking for safe schools and are expressing their displeasure with their feet and pocketbooks.  They walking out of public schools with their children and placing them in "safer" private institutions.  The number of private school students has grown from 2.4 million in 1981 to more than 3.3 million last year.  In addition, more than 700,000 children are now schooled at home.  This move comes at great cost to parents because the average private school tuition is $6,400 annually.  <p>
A decade ago parents considered discipline a very important factor in choosing their children's school.  Mr. Bauer's study found that 85.6 percent of public school parents and 87.1 percent of private school parents considered discipline when choosing a school.<p>

Today, a vast majority of parents (84%) believe that "problems affecting children have grown worse."  A larger majority (92%) of parents feel that there is "more violence in the schools [today] than when they were growing up."  Because they are concerned for the physical safety of their children due to the widespread availability of guns and the resulting violence, they are taking action to protect them.<p>

A May 1994 nationwide poll commissioned by the Family Research Council found that 83 percent of Americans favor giving parents the right to select the safest available school for their children.  This overwhelming support for school choice demonstrates that school safety is an important issue for parents.<p>
<h3><center><a name="root">THE ROOT OF SCHOOL VIOLENCE</a></h3></center>
The American Federation of Teachers captured the essence of the problem when it stated, "Discipline problems both cause and are caused by a growing gap between school and home.  They are exacerbated by faulty public school policies framed by students' rights advocates who have been so preoccupied with protecting the difficult child that they have failed to consider the rights of the average child to learn in a disciplined, structured place."<p>
Unfortunately, a minority of disruptive and too often violent students are spoiling the system for children, who, if given a fighting chance, would succeed.<p>

Deborah Prothrow-Stith, a public health official and author of <u><i>Deadly Consequence</i>s</u>, stated, "[i]f all the children born in America learned at home how to manage anger and aggression non-violently, our homicide and assault rates would decline by 50 percent -- maybe even 75 percent."<p>
<h3><center><a name="conclusion">CONCLUSION</a></center></h3>
Violence is a problem that begins at home and spreads to the community.  Much of the increase in violence in this country and in the schools is due to "changing family situations."  These changes include a lack of parental caring and supervision, lack of discipline on the part of parents, lack of parental concern regarding student behavior and student whereabouts, poor family discipline, and a lack of connectedness with an extended family.<p>

Many children experience difficulty in school because they are emotionally incapacitated by the explosive drama at home.  This is especially true for a growing segment of students from single-parent families.  These children are two to three times as likely as children in two-parent families to have emotional and behavioral problems: they drop out of high school more often, get pregnant as teenagers, abuse drugs, and more often get into trouble with the law.  And most single-parent families are headed by mothers who cannot provide the paternal direction young boys desperately need.<p>
According to Charles Murray, a Bradley Fellow at the American Enterprise Institute, the growing number of fatherless boys creates a "Lord of the Flies" culture evidenced by widespread physical violence, immediate gratification, and predatory sex.  These problems are all-too-evident in America's schools today.<p>
Parents must take responsibility for the rearing of their children and support teachers who need a disciplined classroom to teach.  If parents do their job, then the teacher finds creating a good learning environment easier.<p>
Mary Bruce, a spokeswoman for the Federation of Women's Teachers Associations of Ontario, says teachers must begin early.  She states, "The guns and knives at secondary school get all the attention, but those violent acts were born years earlier in elementary school."<p>
Her observation rings true for many teachers.  Children cultivate a proclivity for violence during the elementary school years and too often those schools tolerate misbehavior which grows more violent with time.  Children need to understand what is acceptable behavior and school authorities need the authority to create a positive learning environment which gives each child the opportunity to learn without fear of verbal and physical intimidation and assault.<p>

Ten years ago, the U.S. Education Department warned the nation that the classroom was seriously handicapped by violence.  The problem is worse today.  School administrators, teachers, law enforcement officials, parents, and teachers must work together to reclaim the classroom for education.  Building well-disciplined schools begins with parents taking responsibility for rearing their children to respect one another and other adults, and it takes school policies which facilitate a climate of discipline.  This combination will promote learning and protect children during their formative years.<p>
[ <a href="welcome.html.cgi">Introduction</a> ]<br>

<center>	***</center>

<i>Robert L. Maginnis is a policy analyst in the Cultural Studies Project at the Family Research Council.</i>
