<html>
<head>
<title>OP-ED FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<h3>OP-ED FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
CONTACT:  DAVID CHAMBERLIN<br>
		202-393-2100<br></h3>
<h2><center>WHEN ALL ELSE FAILS,<br> RESTRUCTURE:</h2>
<h3>INTERPRETING THE NEW SAT SCORES</h3>	</center>

<h4><center><i>by</i><br>
<i>Gary L. Bauer</i></center>
</h4>
<hr size="3" width="30%"><br>
The results are in, the scores are up, and the education establishment is patting itself on the back.  Last week the College Board announced the results from its annual college entrance exam, the SAT.  But this year there's a twist:  this is SAT I, a new but comparable (according to test makers) version of the SAT.  Except SAT I has fewer questions.  And allows students 30 more minutes to take the test.  And permits calculators, and throws out antonyms, one of the most difficult verbal sections on the test.  As the folks at Oldsmobile might say, this is not your father's SAT. <p>  

Why the change in format?  The College Board claims changes were necessary to keep the test in sync "with what and how students are learning today."  Given that explanation, SAT I provides an interesting and accurate commentary on schools today.  Students are spending more time in school and learning less.  One has only to compare a sixth grade reader from the early 20th century to a modern middle school language arts text to verify that 12-year-olds in today's schools are not held to the same standard  their predecessors were.  Rote learning and memorization, such as learning basic math tables and vocabulary, are disparaged.  Crutches like calculators provide ways around such basic tasks.  Many students do not know what an antonym is, let alone understand the nuances of words well enough to determine their opposites.<p>

If the knowledge level of American students is down, as a 30-point drop in SAT verbal scores over two decades indicates, then common sense would prescribe a no-nonsense, back-to-basics, rigorous academic regimen.  If students can't do basic math without a calculator, then teach them their multiplication tables.  Write them, say them, or sing them, but have the students learn them.  If students have puny, bland 
vocabularies, introduce them to works of literature that will keep them striving toward mastery of our English language.  Learning is training, and any athlete knows training involves a lot of sweat and some discomfort, but the results can be exhilarating. <p> 

The pursuit of knowledge is arduous, for both teacher and student.  It requires determination, commitment, and high expectations from parents, teachers, and students.  It cannot be induced with spending or any other form of bureaucratic bribery.  It does not provide a quick fix.  Because long-term solutions to our country's educational woes involve a great deal of lag time before reaping results, most political regimes have found them unappealing.  After all, most administrations pursue an agenda that brings them credit and reelection, which makes quick turnaround time essential.  <p>

The agenda of the day is education restructuring, a term that has quietly been interchanged with education reform.  If education restructuring implied innovative thinking unconstrained by the model of the current public school system, I would have little argument.  We need to restructure the public school system to decrease the federal role and restore local schools, and we need competitive alternatives to public schools.  <p>

In reality, restructuring has only changed the system to <i>make student performance look better</i>.  Goals 2000 marks the height of the restructuring agenda. It created a framework for a new federal-state-local partnership, giving more weight than ever to the federal government.  Goals 2000-style restructuring manipulates the system so that all students can achieve to the same "high" standards.  To make standards universally attainable, they must be lowered to the least common denominator among students.  This is the epitome of Outcome-Based Education, where students are held at the same level until the group is ready to move on as a whole.  <p>

If academic standards were lowered independently of all other factors, falling performance on standardized tests would be noticeable--as it has been on the SAT in recent years--and Americans would blow the whistle on the restructuring agenda.  However, if new tests keyed to the new standards were implemented, performance on these tests would be pleasingly high relative to previous test scores, and the public would be pacified.  That's exactly why Goals 2000 calls for the creation of standards and "aligned assessments." <p> 

That's also what we've witnessed in the SAT overhaul.  Rather than remaining an objective, independent measure, the restructured SAT has been keyed to the restructured classroom.  Results, therefore, will be higher and Americans will be artificially confident that we have finally gotten back on track from our educational waywardness.<p>

That is exactly what President Bill Clinton and Secretary Richard Riley were hoping we'd believe.  They now have the statistics to give the appearance that their education agenda has been a success.  Unfortunately, what has been accomplished is the gerrymandering of objective measures and accepted standards, making it difficult to determine the true status of student achievement.  Instead of rallying Americans to the task of real education reform, our leaders are prodding us into that blissful Lake Wobegon naivete that sees all our children as decidedly above average. <p>

- -8/29/95<p><br>
[ <a href="welcome.html.cgi">Introduction</a> ]<br>
[ <a href="http://www.townhall.com/townhall/FRC/welcome.html>Family Research Council</a> ]<p>

 <center>***</center><br>

<i>Gary L. Bauer, former domestic policy advisor to President Reagan and Under Secretary of Education, is President of the Family Research Council, a Washington, DC -based research and advocacy organization.</i>

