</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>CHEATING SCANDAL POINTS TO
	MORAL DECLINE</title>
<center><h2>CHEATING SCANDAL POINTS TO<br>
	MORAL DECLINE</h2></center>
	<h4><center><i>by</i><br>
	<i>Robert L. Maginnis</i></h4></center>
<hr size="3" width="30%"><br>
Cheating scandals at the nation's military academies make news because military officers are supposed to epitomize loyalty, integrity and selfless service.  This is evidenced by the schools' strict honor codes, which are unsurpassed in academe.<p>  

The announcement of the U.S. Naval Academy's widest cheating scandal in its 149 year history suggests an erosion of the military profession's reliability, and testifies to the decline in America's culture.  The Navy convened a special review board to investigate charges that up to 134 midshipmen illegally had advance knowledge about the contents of an electrical engineering final examination given in December 1992.  The board recommended expulsion of 29 midshipmen and lesser punishment for 42 others.<p>    

Advance knowledge of the contents of an exam is a violation of the academy's honor code, which states that midshipmen must not lie, cheat or steal or tolerate those who do.  The code serves to impress upon future naval leaders that a high standard is expected of those who must make life-and-death decisions.  A similar code applies to the other academies, and they too have suffered scandals in recent years.<p>

If future military leaders can't deal honestly with school exams, how will they perform in situations that could cost lives?  In America's combat history, the character of our leaders has often been more powerful than the firepower of our weapons.<p>     

For years, the nation's military academies took America's best and integrated them into a military regimen.  The process was simplified because applicants shared similar, well-defined ideas of right and wrong.  Today, however, there is a tremendous chasm between the values required of a professional military and those possessed by the pool of eligible college-age students.  The process of integrating and indoctrinating-- bridging the chasm-- is more difficult than ever before.<p>
  
This phenomenon goes beyond the military and affects the civilian sector as well.  Industry, business, academe, government and family all rely, like the military, on people with integrity, commitment, candor, discipline, selfless service and competence.  <p>  
                                                                                              

The erosion of values is traceable largely to changes in institutions which have traditionally been responsible for imparting them to our youth.  These key institutions include family, school, church, media and government. <p> 

<ul><li>The typical American family of the 1950s consisted of a working father, a stay-at-home mother and one or two children.  Nearly 70 percent of all households used to fit that description.  Today, nearly two-thirds of the nation's young children still are raised at home by full-time mothers or mothers who are employed part-time outside of the home.  Women are increasingly pressured, however, to work full-time in the paid labor force.  And work force competition for material benefits has reduced the time that fathers have with their children. </ul><p> 

Armand Nicholi, a Harvard psychiatrist, believes that "the character development and emotional stability of a person...is [the product] of the relationship he experiences as a child with both of his parents."  The importance of parent-child time for childrearing was confirmed in a survey commissioned by the Massachusetts Mutual Insurance Company which found that Americans believe "parents having less time to spend with their families" is the single most important reason for the family's decline in our society. <p>

Although the length of the work week has changed little in recent years, the rise of more mothers joining working fathers reduces parent-child time.  Additionally, the dual wage earning couple often leave their children with day-care providers despite a 1993 Family Research Council survey finding that 87 percent of Americans agree that young children benefit more from mother care than substitute care.  Choosing inferior child care alternatives during the child's most impressionable and value forming years is risky. <p>

Today, one in six families is headed by a single mother.  Increasing numbers of children are being born out of wedlock.  The illegitimacy rate is 22 percent for white babies and 68 percent for black babies.  Growing up in single-parent households too often means financial hardship and a serious lack of parental attention, from absent fathers.<p>

The U.S. has the highest divorce rate in the world -- 5.3 divorces per 1,000 people.  The consequences of divorce for children are significant.  Not only does the child's standard of living usually change for the worse, there is also a loss of parental attention; many children in divorced homes require psychological help.  Girls from divorced families are at much greater risk for early sexual initiation, promiscuity, non-marital pregnancies, venereal diseases, and divorce than are girls in two-parent intact families.  Boys in similar situations are at greater risk of dropping out of school than girls, and are also more likely to exhibit aggressive behavior.<p>

The traumas of abuse and neglect are frequently associated with divorce.  A National Institute of Justice study found that people who had been "abused or neglected as children are more likely to be arrested as juveniles, as adults, and for violent crimes."  Another study found that chronic exposure to violence, in the home or in the neighborhood, often can lead to violent behavior.<p>

The family as a value-influencing institution has been weakened, and children bear the brunt of parental mistakes with an inevitable impact on their value system.<p>
 
<ul><li>The school is the second most important contributor to the child's value system.  Modern educators, however, are spending more and more time on remedial social work.  Instead of equipping America's youth academically for the next century, educators are counseling their pupils about drug abuse, discipline problems, sex, suicide and anorectic and bulimic disorders.  Surveys indicate that the biggest problems in public schools today are drugs and crime.  Thirty years ago, chewing gum and talking in class were the major problems.</ul>

A national survey of college freshmen found a significant shift in motivation away from altruism and toward concern with making money and getting power and status.  Not surprisingly, students are finding it easier to rationalize lying or cheating in pursuit of their goals.<p>

Theodore Roosevelt stated, "To educate a person in mind and not in morals is to educate a menace to society."  Ethics training was replaced in the last 20 years by values clarification programs which treat children like adults who need only to clarify values rather than to acquire them.  At best, values clarification encourages the student to close the gap between the values he professes and his personal action.  At worst, it promotes moral relativism.<p>

The school's role as a value instiller has changed.  There is, however, a growing national momentum to require schools to introduce "character" instruction.  Whether or not this trend is positive, however, depends upon whose values prevail.<p>

<ul><li>Until the early 1960s, organized religion was very influential in most children's value-formation process.  Today, however, although most Americans claim to be religious, fewer are regularly attending religious services.  This trend has been especially evident during times of great change, particularly over the last decade.</ul><p>

For many, the church is no longer the center of family and community life.  Theology has become more relativistic in many churches, and its focus has correspondingly been altered for many people.  Members now more often expect to be served, as opposed to being challenged to serve others.  Churches are increasingly functioning as a "country club" or "social club" that scratches the religious itch and provides a drive-through "feel-good" service rather than as a center of salvation and substantive, community-building activity.<p>

The influence of organized religions has waned, and nontraditional movements have emerged, such as the New Age Movement, a post-Christian belief system that recycles elements of eastern mysticism with modern, self-centered philosophy.<p>

This fast-growing spiritual, social and political movement seeks to transform individuals and society.  It has left its mark on sociology, theology, medicine, anthropology, history, sports and literature.  The New Age movement promotes a view of reality that admits to no absolutes.  Many adherents believe that good and evil are essentially one, thus breeding moral relativism. <p>

<ul><li>The all-pervasive media also influence society's values.  Television, with its 6,600 cable systems, leaves a daily impression on most children.  The average child spends more time in front of the television than in school.  Television includes Saturday morning cartoons such as the Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles and Ghost Busters -- programs that promote aggressive and disrespectful behavior.  Afternoon television provides false views of life via soap operas and sex-saturated talk shows.  Evening programming often promotes anti-family agendas, and glorifies promiscuity, violence, homosexuality, and more. </ul><p>

The average teenager in the U.S. sees 50 R-rated movies a year.  Some of these are rated "R" because of violence.  "True Romance," for example, depicts a man killing his wife's former pimp by shooting him point-blank, first in the groin and then in the face.  The wife applauds the act.<p>

Rap music is another virtual obsession with today's teens.  "2 Live Crew" has an album, "Nasty As They Wanna be," which features strings of obscenities set to music.  Women are described only as sex objects for the singer's gratification.  The album includes many explicit references to male and female genitalia and even sexual torture of women.<p>   

<ul><li>Finally, government exists to reflect the will of the people in the laws and to enforce those laws.  Unfortunately, government's track record has been poor,  particularly with regard to public safety.  Elected officials pass many laws, hire more policemen and build more prisons, but the crime problem is not abating.  </ul><p>

The government also lacks the discipline, like too many individual Americans, to balance its budget.  This communicates a message of fiscal irresponsibility.  Opinion polls place politicians and government bureaucrats at the bottom of lists of occupations ranked for trust and confidence.  This reflects a growing cynicism about those in civil authority.<p>

The breakdown of value-influencing institutions was recently linked to the Navy's scandal by Sean M. Fahey, the 21-year-old senior who, as brigade commander, holds the highest rank among the 4,200 midshipmen at Annapolis.  He states, "The idea of integrity wasn't that hard to grasp.  Now, institutionally, we've hardly changed.  But the whole world has turned upside down.  Our class -- we grew up at a time when nobody in our entire lives, in any institution, was ever there to tell us what's right or wrong."<p>

Mr. Fahey explains the significance of the value chasm for the Navy.  "The sea is the same sea now as it was 2,000 years ago," he says, "A storm will tear apart a ship just as it did 2,000 years ago.  If you go out to sea and people die because you were not good at your word, it means everything."<p>

This future officer understands the tough job that faces every American leader, military or civilian.  Our current crop of young Americans are products of institutions that have failed to instill important values.  This has grave consequences for America.<p><br>
[ <a href="welcome.html.cgi">Introduction</a> ]<br>
[ <a href="http://www.townhall.com/townhall/FRC/welcome.html>Family Reaseach Council</a> ]<p>
<center>	***</center>

<i>Robert L. Maginnis is a retired Army officer and a graduate of the United States Military Academy.  He is a policy analyst in the Cultural Studies Project at the Family Research Council.</i>

</html>
</body>
