<head>
<title>TH Spotlight on The Leader: Congressman Dick Armey</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
August 21, 1995
<h2>TH Spotlight on The Leader</h2>
</center>
<hr size="5" width="70%">
<p>
Congressman Dick Armey is "one of his party's most prolific and effective idea machines," according of the Wall Street Journal.  His former colleague Vin Weber calls him a "one-man think tank in cowboy boots."
<p>
With his unanimous election as the first Republican Majority Leader since 1954, Armey continued the string of victories that, in just ten years, has transformed him from a little-known economics professor into a leading figure in national politics.
<p>
As principal architect of the Republican "Contract with America," Armey palyed a key role in helping his party win majority control of the House and Senate in 1994.  When he and then -Minority Whip Newt Gingrich decided to present America with a ten-point agenda to be considered in the first 100 days of a Republican Majority, Armey supervised the drafting of the Contract bills and then worked tirelessly to gather  wide public support for the effort.
<p>
Armey is well-known for the flat-tax proposal.  Under his plan, all income would be taxed at a flat 17-percent rate, with no credits or exemptions for low-income earners and children.  A family of four earning $38,600 would pay no federal income tax.  "You could pay your taxes on a form the size of a postcard," he says.
<p>
Armey first came to national prominence through his advocacy of  free-market, pro-growth policies, and his attacks on wasteful federal spending programs.  His 1988 base-closure legislation broke a decade-old log-jam in Congress, enabling the Pentagon to shut down hundreds of obselete military facilities.  Two years later, Armey led a bipartisan coaltion oposing outdated farm programs, an effort which saved taxpayers over $14 billion.  For his budget-cutting efforts, U.S. News and World Report named him an "unsung hero."
<p>
Armey has consistantly advanced and defended the philosophy of President Ronald Reagan.  In 1990, when taxes and regulations were once again on the rise, Armey led House Republicans in opposing the "Budget  Summit Tax Increase" and the re-regulation of the economy.  As the ranking Republican on the Joint Economic Committee in 1991-92, he argued vigorously that Americans of all income classes would benefit instead from lower taxes and economic freedom.
<p>
Following the GOP's 1992 defeats, Armey ran for Conference Chairman, the third-ranking position in the House GOP leadership, arguing the party needed more assertive conservative leadership.  Suprising most pundits, he beats the incumbant, 88 to 84, with strong support from the newly-elected freshman.
<p>
In 1994, Armey's north Dallas district reelected him with 77 percent of the vote.  A native of Cando, N.D., he has worked at a grain elevator and as a telephone lineman.  He holds a B.A. form Jamestown College (ND), a master's from the University of North Dakota, and a Ph.D. from the University of Oklahoma.  He is a former chairman of the University of Texas economics depatment.
<p>
In his new book, The Freedom Revolution, Representative Armey describes the Republican victory in November of 1994 as, "...in every sense, a Freedom Revolution -- a revolution in the bold sense of scrapping an entrenched, arrogant political order, of tossing out the moneychangers.  But, even more, a revolution in the humbler sense of revolving back to our points of origin.  A revolution not so much in power as in faith -- the faith of our fathers."  As Representative Armey states, "This is not a moment for the timid," and through his great writings and speeches one can clearly see that the Leader stands poised on the front lines of the Freedom Revolution.
<p>
<center>
<a name="speeches"><h3>Speeches</h3></a>
</center>
<ul>
<li><a href="/townhall/spotlights/8-21-95/sp-npc.html">July 19, 1995</a> -- "The Flat Tax in Our Future" Address by Congressman Dick Armey on Reintroducing the Freedom and Fairness Restoration Act -- National Press Club.
<li><a href="/townhall/spotlights/8-21-95/rrtoast.html">May 17, 1995</a> -- Toast by Congressman Armey -- American Spectator Tribute to Ronald Reagan.
<li><a href="/townhall/spotlights/8-21-95/sp-cato.html">May 9, 1995</a> -- Address by Congressman Dick Armey At the Dedication of the Hayek Auditorium -- Cato Institute.
<li><a href="/townhall/spotlights/8-21-95/sp-cpac.html">February 10, 1995</a> -- Address by Congressman Dick Armey -- Conservative Political Action Conference.
<li><a href="/townhall/spotlights/8-21-95/sp-clc.html">December 3, 1994</a> -- Address by Congressman Dick Armey -- Conservative Leadership Conference.
</ul>
<p>
