<html>
<head>
<title>The Flat Tax in Our Future</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>"The Flat Tax in Our Future"</h2>
<b>Address by Congressman Dick Armey<br>
on Reintroducing the Freedom and Fairness Restoration Act<br>
National Press Club<br>
Washington, D.C.<br>
July 19, 1995<br></b></center>
<hr>
<p>
Ladies and gentlemen, I hope you'll forgive me for being in such a cheerful mood.  But to paraphrase that old Ethel Merman song, "Everything's coming up flat tax."  
<p>
One of my rules of thumb is when Dick Gephardt is singing out of Dick Armey's hymnal, you know something important is going on out there.  And it's not just Dick Gephardt.  These days it seems you can't swing a dead catfish in this town without hitting the author of a flat-tax plan, or at least a major tax overhaul.  Clearly, the lessons of the Contract with America are being heard loud and clear by the Washington establishment.  The American people are clamoring for a dramatically different kind of government -- one that's smaller, more open, and more accountable.
<p>
As I said in my new book, The Freedom Revolution, I believe the most enduring revolutions bring about the simplest reforms.  The moment the polls closed on November 8th, 1994, today's mindlessly complicated, growth-stifling tax code began tumbling toward the waste-paper basket of history.  And that's why my friend Senator Richard Shelby of Alabama and I are proud today to reintroduce the Freedom and Fairness Restoration Act.  
<p>
This legislation features a tax system so simple you could do your taxes on a postcard, and so fair, it might just restore people's ability to trust their government.  Wouldn't that be a nice change?  Rather than tinkering, Senator Shelby and I scrap the entire code, corporate and personal, and replace it with one flat rate that applies to all Americans.  We leave just one exception: a family allowance to ensure that every family has the first claim to its own income sufficient to support itself.  A typical family of four must earn $33,300 before it owes a penny of federal income tax.  Beyond that, everyone pays a flat 17 percent on all income.  No deductions.  No loopholes.  No tax breaks.  No tables.  No schedules.  No nothing.  
<p>
Each year, you calculate your income, fill out a postcard-size form like the one blown up on this chart, make out a check, and drop it in the mail.  End of process.  You're done with the IRS until next year.  It's as simple as an income tax gets.
<p>
If you have business income, the process is almost identical.  Whether you're IBM or a mom-and-pop grocer, you still fill out a postcard-sized form.  Just subtract expenses from revenues and pay 17 percent on the remainder.  That's it.  Instead of taking eleven hours to do your taxes, as the average family does today, you could do it in eleven minutes.  Maybe less.
<p>
Imagine the new world that will dawn.  Gone will be today's 480 different tax forms, and the 280 forms that explain how to fill out the 480 forms.  Whole armies of tax attorneys and lobbyists will be out looking for more productive work.  And as for all those IRS agents and auditors?  Well, instead of harassing you, they'll be sitting silently at their desks, like Maytag Repairmen, feeling bored and, I suspect, just a little lonely.
<p>
There is an important change from last year's bill.  We've added a new provision that requires a three-fifths supermajority to raise the rate, add additional rates, create loopholes, or shrink the family allowance.  We are absolutely determined that the flat tax stay flat.
<p>
And I can tell you, this idea is catching fire.  You can feel it.  The flat tax is in America's future.  Why am I so confident?  Well, for one thing, over the past year, I've received more than 5,000 intensely enthusiastic letters praising the bill.  And in just the past month, I've received nearly that many messages over the Internet.  Yes, the flat tax has gone "third wave" with its very own home page on the worldwide web.  The address is armey.flattax.
<p>
From this mail, I can tell you there are four basic reasons why people like the flat tax.  They know it's simple, it's honest, it's pro-growth, and it's fair -- four virtues notably lacking in our current system.
<p>
First of all, as I've said, it's incredibly simple.  No longer will the American people spend anything like 5.4 billion man-hours figuring their taxes each year, which incidentally is more man-hours than it takes to produce every car, van, and truck built in the United States.  By one estimate, this needless time and paperwork costs our economy a staggering $232 billion a year, more than the entire federal deficit.  That's a potential savings of $900 for every man, woman, and child in America.
<p>
Second, unlike today's code, the flat tax is honest.  By sweeping away all the special-interest loopholes, it shows us right up front how much government is really costing us.  And by eliminating the code's social engineering and economic tinkering, it shifts power from politicians to private citizens.  It has the decency to respect our ability to make our own financial judgments.
<p>
Third, the flat tax is incredibly pro-growth, planting the seeds for rapid rises in output and wages.  Any professional economist worth his Ph.D. will tell you the chief cause of stagnant wages is our nation's anemic saving rate.  And the chief cause of our low saving rate is today's destructive policy of taxing savings twice -- once when a dollar is earned, and then again when it produces a return.  The flat tax wipes out this perverse bias against saving in a single bold stroke.  As a result, savings will rise.  The pool of capital will grow.  Workers will be better equipped and trained.  And their output will expand, leading to bigger paychecks.
<p>
But a higher saving rate is not enough.  We also need greater rewards for work and risk-taking, the true engines of wealth-creation.  Instead of punishing entrepreneurship with steeply progressive tax rates, as we do today, the flat tax slashes the top rate from 40 percent to 17, enabling America to unfetter her would-be Thomas Edisons and Bill Gates to create the inventions and industries and high-paying jobs of tomorrow.  Today, people rightly ask themselves why they should invent the proverbial "better mousetrap" when the government is going to take away half their earnings anyway?  The flat tax would make such risks worthwhile, while making America a magnet for foreign investment capital.  As a result, as you can see from this chart, the income of the average American family of four would be approximately $4,300 higher in 2002 than it would if we retained the current system.  Higher savings, more risk-taking, higher wages.
<p>
The fourth and final reason people like the flat tax is also, in my view, the most politically powerful.  It's fair.  Let me tell a quick story.  I was walking out of a hotel in Dallas one day, and the fellow that parks the cars approached me, and he said, "Congressman, I love your flat tax.  And the reason I love your flat tax is it treats everybody the same."  I think that gentleman revealed something very profound, something very American, in his view of fairness.  In America, we define fairness as treating everybody the same.  Rich or poor, black or white, we're all equal.
<p>
That's why liberals ought to love the flat tax.  When you tax everyone at the same rate, the rich pay a lot more in taxes than the middle class or the poor.  With three times the income, you pay three times the taxes.  Ten times the income, ten times the taxes.  And so on.  Now if you ask me, that seems pretty fair.  But even beyond that, by the traditional liberal definition, our flat tax plan is "progressive" -- as progressive as the code we had under President Kennedy.  As the chart shows, thanks to the generous family allowance, even with a flat rate, a family making $33,300 a year would pay no federal income tax, while a family making $50,000 would pay six percent of its income, and a family making 200,000 a year would pay 14 percent of its income.  This means about 20 million lower-income Americans would be dropped from the tax rolls altogether.  What's not for a liberal to love?
<p>
So there you have it.  Simplicity, honesty, growth, fairness -- four reasons people love the flat tax.  But now allow me to take a few minutes to address the four most commonly heard concerns about our plan.
<p>
The first concern comes from the class-warfare crowd -- and, I'm sad to say, a few careless reporters -- who are asserting that the Armey flat tax does not tax investment income.  They say we're letting wealthy stockholders off the tax hook.  This is completely untrue.  Our plan taxes investment income at exactly the same rate as wages.  What we don't do is tax it twice.  
<p>
Take a dollar of corporate-generated earnings.  Today, it's taxed at the business level, and then taxed again when it's paid out as a dividend.  That's double taxation, which, as I've said, depresses the saving rate.  Our bill, by contrast, taxes every dollar of business-generated income at the business level, once and only once.  And it does so far more efficiently than today's system, because it eliminates the need for taxpayers and businesses to keep billions of pieces of paper for reporting purposes.  So let me repeat.  Under our plan, all income is taxed at the same 17 percent rate with no exceptions.  To suggest or imply that we do not tax investment income is a misrepresentation of the plan.
<p>
A second question of concern comes from people who ask, "Will eliminating the home mortgage interest deduction hurt the real-estate industry?"  The answer is "Not as much as lower interest rates will help it."  While our plan does end the interest deduction, it also ends the tax on interest earnings.  As a result, nothing changes.  Both borrowers and lenders are held harmless.  What the homeowner loses in deductions, he gains in lower interest rates.  And in fact he comes out ahead on the deal, because the flat tax ends the bias against saving, causing the capital pool to swell and driving interest rates down even further.  That's good news for the housing industry.
<p>
And frankly, homeowners are not as wedded to this supposedly "sacred" deduction as you might think.  By a three-to-one margin in a recent poll, homeowners said they're willing to forego the mortgage deduction if that loss is offset by a reduction in their tax bill by a similar amount, which our plan does.  So I'm confident homeowners, homebuilders, Realtors, and lenders will all support our approach, knowing they're not losing a tax break -- they're gaining a new and better tax code, and a bigger economy.
<p>
And that leads me to an observation.  Ladies and gentlemen, the American dream is not just owning your own home, it's getting your kids out of it.  We want a high-growth, low-inflation economy with opportunities where our children can get out of school, get a good job, raise their own family, and be able to afford their own home.  And the flat tax goes a long way to helping them realize that dream.
<p>
The third major concern about our plan comes from some of our conservative friends who are worried charity would suffer without the charitable deduction.  My guess is they won't even miss it.  For one thing, almost half of charitable contributions today are not even claimed as deductions, so ending the break would have no effect on that giving.  But more tellingly, during the 1980s, the so-called "decade of greed," charitable giving actually went up even as its value as a tax break declined dramatically.  Because President Reagan cut the top marginal rate from 70 percent to 28 percent, the deduction became far less valuable for tax purposes.  And yet total charitable giving doubled.  Religious contributions nearly tripled.  Why?  Because people had more money in their pockets.  Their taxes were lower, and their incomes higher.  The American people responded to greater freedom and prosperity as they've always done, by opening their hearts and their wallets to their neighbors.
<p>
And finally, the fourth major concern with the flat tax is that it will explode the deficit.  Those who want to preserve the current, complicated tax structure have been repeating an estimate of "$200 billion dollars a year" like a mantra.  Well, as Ronald Reagan used to say, "The trouble with our opponents is not that they are ignorant, but that they know so much that isn't so."  I've said from the beginning that I want our proposal to be debated on its merits, and not on the issue of revenue loss.  I've designed it to provide a $40 billion tax cut, paid for by spending cuts.  I've asked the Joint Committee on Taxation to score our bill.  And I'm confident Joint Tax will find it to be deficit neutral.  When it does, the red herring of revenue loss will be laid to rest for good.
<p>
What, then, is the Freedom and Fairness Restoration Act?  It's a tax plan so simple you could do your taxes on a postcard.  But it's more than that.  It's also a vision of what America can be again -- a formula for rejuvenating our economy, freeing our entrepreneurial talent, and reviving stagnant family wages.  It's a common-sense plan for returning to a government that is simple, honest, and fair to all our citizens.  And who knows?  It might just restore people's ability to trust their government.  And this is why I believe the flat tax is in America's future.
<p>
Thank you.
<p>
[ <a href="i-armey.html#speeches">Spotlight on The Leader</a> ]
<p>
</body>
</html>
