<html>
<head>
<title>Address at CPAC</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Address by Congressman Dick Armey</h2>
<b>Conservative Political Action Conference<br>
Washington, D.C.<br>
February 10, 1995</b><br>
</center>
<hr>
<p>
Thank you, Wayne La Pierre, for that kind introduction.  What a pleasure it is to be here with all of my old friends at CPAC, the real heroes of the Second Reagan Revolution. And what a special pleasure to be a conservative at this exciting time in history.<p>  
Something dramatic is happening in this town.  I've never seen anything like it.  Democrats are falling all over each other to vote for smaller government, middle class tax cuts, the line-item veto, even a balanced budget amendment.  Dick Gephardt is talking about the flat tax.  And President Clinton is reportedly going to name an aircraft carrier the "USS Ronald Reagan."<p>
It all reminds me of that old liberal protest song, "The times, they are a-changin'."  Well, the times are changing, all right.  But not in the direction the liberals were hoping.<p>
America is moving forward, forward to the freedoms envisioned by our Founding Fathers.  Far from being some antiquated, outdated idea from the past, smaller government is really the newest and most radical idea in the long history of human politics.  And thanks to your grass-roots efforts, it's undergoing a long-overdue revival.<p>
I believe we are witnessing one of those great historical transitions when one era sets, and a new, more exciting era dawns, heralding undreamed-of possibilities.  It's a time when the American people are willing to rethink all the old assumptions and dare to entertain the most sweeping change, the kind of change contained in our Contract with America.<p>
Our Contract is based on a simple realization.  Big Government as an idea is finished.  Big Government does not work.  Only freedom works.  Whether the issue is poverty, crime, health care, education, or the environment, freedom offers a better outcome than does government.  How do I know freedom works?  Because you can't help noticing a difference between the Post Office and Federal Express.<p>  
How do I know freedom works?  Because in the 1980s this nation spent one-third more, in real terms, on government monopoly schools.  And test scores went down.  Meanwhile, private schools and even home-schooling parents are turning out Harvard material on shoestring budgets.<p>
How do I know freedom works?  Because 30 years and five trillion dollars in welfare spending have produced a permanent underclass, fatherless families, skyrocketing crime rates, and one out of every three babies being born out-of-wedlock.  Meanwhile, churches and charities are out there actually solving these problems and changing lives, at a fraction of the cost.  To paraphrase my friend and hero, Thomas Sowell, we don't have faith in freedom,
we have evidence.<p>
If you think about it, the Founding Fathers are still the world's only true progressives.  The socialists, the environmentalists, the multiculturalists, the labor-union monopolists, the so-called consumer advocates, the central planners of all stripes, these are the real reactionaries of our day.  Their idea of progress is more government control.  But George Washington's idea of progress was more freedom.  And that's the philosophy behind our Contract with America.  We firmly believe what Ronald Reagan said so many years ago:  "There is no such thing as a left or right.  There is only an up or down: up to man's age-old dream, the ultimate in individual freedom consistent with law and order -- or down to the ant-heap of totalitarianism."<p>
Well, tonight, I'm happy to report that in these first, busy 38 days, America has begun slowly moving upward.  We've racked up win after win on our Contract.  We've picked up 50 to 70 Democrats on almost every bill.  Meanwhile, the left-wing liberals are, to quote that old Frank Sinatra song, "bewitched, bothered, and bewildered."<p>
On Day One, the longest opening day in the history of the House, we overhauled our rules from top to bottom.  To ensure accountability, we made Congress obey the same laws it imposes on the private sector.  We banned closed-door committee meetings and put an end to ghost voting.  To promote efficiency, we abolished dozens of committees and subcommittees,
cut out hundreds of staff positions, and swept away all those frivolous commemorative bills like "National Asparagus Day" and "Pizza and Pasta Week."  To keep ourselves honest, we reformed our budget terminology, so that from now on, the term "spending cut" will actually mean a cut, and not just a smaller increase.  And best of all, to safeguard the American taxpayer, we passed a rule requiring a three-fifths supermajority to raise income taxes.  And that was just Day One.<p>
Being federalists, naturally we've moved quickly to restore the proper balance of power between Washington and the states, with a bill that effectively bans unfunded federal mandates.  From now on, if Congress wants the sovereign states or private citizens to do something, Congress is going to have to provide the funds or just not do it.<p>
And because we believe the federal government should limit itself strictly to those activities which are truly national in scope, it was a distinct pleasure for us this week to present to President Reagan a very special birthday gift, the line-item veto.<p>
Perhaps the most deeply held conviction we conservatives cherish is a belief in self-restraint, national as well as personal.  We disdain government borrowing.  We reject President Roosevelt's famous quip that "we merely owe it to ourselves."  The truth of the matter is we're spending our children's inheritance.  Today's deficit is tomorrow's tax increase.  Right now, every child in America is carrying $18,000 in federal national debt.  And that's why, in my view, the crowning achievement of these first 38 days has been our passage of a Balanced Budget Amendment to the Constitution.<p>
Without this amendment, the focused and well-organized special interests will always be able to combine to defeat the widely dispersed and unfocused public interest.  Only if members of Congress have no legal choice but to set priorities, accept tradeoffs, and cut spending, can we resist the temptation to raid our posterity's piggy banks.<p>
Now, as you know, in passing the amendment, we lost the tax-limitation clause.  I was very, very disappointed.  But let me assure you.  We will return to fight another day on this issue.  We have already scheduled April 15, 1996, as the day we will vote on a tax-limitation amendment to the United States Constitution.<p>
And we've got plenty of other votes scheduled, too.  We have 62 more days to go.  And there are plenty of exciting changes in store.  Allow me to mention just a few.<p>
The crime problem is caused by criminals , not impersonal social forces.  So we'll pass a crime bill that funds more police and prisons, not basketball and ballet classes.<p>
Families are the fundamental unit of society.  They should have the first claim on their own hard-earned dollars.  So we'll vote to let families lower their yearly tax bill by $500 per child.	The economy is being strangled by excessive regulation.  So we'll vote on a sweeping regulatory reform bill to, in effect, legalize capitalism in the United States.<p>
The nation is saddled with too many lawsuits pleasing too many trial lawyers.  So we'll vote on a strong legal-reform bill that I call "Dan Quayle's revenge."<p>
The welfare system has become a source of out-of-wedlock births and family breakdown, which in turn promotes social breakdown, gangs, drugs, violence, and despair. We've been so busy imposing our idea of compassion, we've never bothered to stop and think of what effect our actions are having on young children.<p>  
So we'll vote on a sweeping Personal Responsibility Act that will abolish upwards of 70 existing federal welfare programs and entitlements, including the big one, AFDC.  Then we'll take the money this saves, cut it by ten percent, cap it, and send it back to the states with virtually no strings attached.  The only restrictions we'll put on the money are as follows: "You must spend it to help the needy.  You cannot give cash to unwed teenage mothers.  And you cannot give it to able-bodied people who refuse to work."  And that's it.  This is a "tough love" solution that really will end welfare as we know it.<p>
Finally, because the Founding Fathers would be shocked and dismayed by a Congress of politicians-for-life, we will hold the first-ever vote on term limits.  Now, I have to tell you this is going to be a tough fight.  Making term limits a reality will take all of our resources, and all of our energies, and every last drop of commitment we can muster.  And, as in the past, we do count on your help.<p>
Obviously, the Contract with America is not a timid document.  In fact, the Contract will do more to dismantle the welfare-regulatory state in 100 days than anything I've seen in my ten years in Congress.  But as President Reagan used to say, "You ain't seen nothin' yet."  It's after the first hundred days that the fun really begins.
<p>  
Come May, you will see some of the most dramatic changes in government anyone can remember.  We'll pass a huge 1996 budget resolution and 13 appropriations bills that I think you'll find very pleasing.  I can't give you all the details tonight, but, for starters, how does defunding the National Endowment for the Arts sound?  Not just cut, defund.  And what would you say if we privatized the Corporation for Public Broadcasting?  And let me ask you this.  What if we dismantled the Department of Education?  How about if we turned off the lights at the Department of Energy?  How about Commerce?  How about HUD?  How about the Post Office?  
<p>
And ladies and gentlemen, I would be remiss if I didn't mention farm subsidies, helium subsidies, Amtrak, mass transit, Davis-Bacon, Legal Services, the REA, the TVA, the EDA, the ICC, and the MPP.<p>  
And I'm not through yet.  Allow me to ask your opinion on one last thing.  Ladies and gentlemen, are you interested in scrapping the Internal Revenue Code and replacing it with a flat tax?<p>
As I've said all along, the Contract with America is merely the shakedown cruise for the Counter-Revolution.  Of course, in order to make the voyage, the ship must first make it safely out of port.  If we're going to achieve these sweeping reforms I just mentioned, we must first win the lasting trust of a rightly suspicious public.  And to do that, we must fulfill our Contract with America.  All our dreams, all our hopes for our children's future, hang on these next 62 days.<p>  
These are amazing times, when a whole new era is cresting the horizon.  And sweeping change is in the air.  Tonight, the course of freedom runs more swiftly, and our future shines more brightly, than we dared imagine just yesterday.<p>
Many years ago, when we conservatives were on the fringes of political life, in a speech that still rings in my memory, Barry Goldwater urged our fledgling forces to fight on, "until our cause has won the day, inspired the world, and shown the way to a tomorrow worthy of all our yesteryears."<p>
Well, my friends, we have won the day. We have inspired the world.  And tonight we have it in our power to make real, the tomorrow Barry Goldwater could only dare to dream.  So let us renew our resolve.  Let us quicken our pace. And arm in arm, we will secure the rebirth of freedom.<p>
Thank you, and God bless you.
<p>
[ <a href="i-armey.html#speeches">Spotlight On the Leader</a> ]
<p>
</body>
</html>


