<html>
<title>The Summer MediScare Campaign: Subsidized By The American Taxpayers -- Heritage </title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">

<b>Government Integrity Project Report No. 4<br>
August 9, 1995</b>
<p>
<center>
<H2>The Summer MediScare Campaign: Subsidized By The American Taxpayers</H2><p>

By <a href="/heritage/staff/wittmann.htm">Marshall Wittmann</a><br>
Senior Fellow in Congressional Affairs<br> 
<a href="/heritage/">The Heritage Foundation</a>
<p>
Charles P. Griffin<br>
Deputy House Liaison</center><br>
<p>

As the Senate prepares to join the House in Congress's August recess, it has become clear that myriad interest groups have united to frighten senior citizens into believing that attempts to reform the Medicare system are really an attempt to "steal" their health care.  The fact that the Trustees of the Medicare Trust Funds -- among them three members of President Clinton's Cabinet -- have predicted the imminent bankruptcy of this health care safety net for the elderly has done nothing to dissuade the opponents of reform.
<p>
The catch is that many of the special interests now attempting to instill fear in the nation's senior citizens are subsidized by the American taxpayer.  In effect, elderly Americans are helping to fund  a campaign of lobbying and propaganda that runs directly counter to their own long-term best interests.
<p>
A June 27, 1995, "Medicare Message" distributed by the House Democratic Leadership refers to six taxpayer-subsidized organizations actively involved in the effort to "talk about the devastating effects of the Republican Medicare cuts."  These organizations received nearly $80 million in federal funding between July 1993 and June 1994:
<ul>
<p>
<li>AFL-CIO<br> 
$2,038,000
<p>
<li>Families USA 
<br>$250,000
<p>
<li>Service Employees International Union (SEIU)<br>
$137,000
<p>
<li>Save Our Security<br>
$100,000
<p>
<li>American Association of Retired Persons (AARP)<br>
$76,000,000
<p>
<li>American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees (AFSCME)<br>
$148,000
</ul>
<p>
One day later, on June 28, the National Committee to Preserve Social Security and Medicare ($75,000) wrote a letter to Members of Congress opposing the conference report on the budget resolution.  The organization's president, Martha McSteen, wrote that the Medicare reforms in that bill would "seriously harm" the program and that "reductions of this magnitude are only necessary to ... balance the budget by 2002."  She went on to say that "these reductions do not reflect the budget priorities of Americans."
<p>
In an attempt to influence the outcome of the debate in Congress over Medicare, some taxpayer-funded organizations have resorted to aggressive grassroots activity.  For example, four busloads of SEIU members joined Representative John Lewis (D-GA) in disrupting an August 7 Medicare meeting attended by members of the Georgia congressional delegation.  In addition, the SEIU, Urban League ($6,447,000), and Teamsters ($3,542,000) were among the organizations that led a large protest in front of House Budget Committee Chairman John Kasich's office in Ohio on July 21.  Speaking at the event, where 20 demonstrators were arrested, John Sweeney (candidate for the presidency of the federally subsidized AFL-CIO) stated, "We are here today to deliver a message to John Kasich, Newt Gingrich and every right-wing Republican and turncoat Democrat" in Congress that "we will not allow you to destroy job training and education and Medicare and Medicaid."<i>1</i>
<p>
Other organizations have targeted other Members of Congress.  In New York, taxpayer-subsidized AFSCME launched a "four day TV blitz" in mid-July targetted at Representative Jack Quinn (R-NY) to show that the results of proposed Medicare reforms will be "catastrophic."  According to press reports, "the 30-second spot, which will air 37 times ... features a couple distraught over 'Republican efforts' to cut health benefits for the elderly." A spokesman for the Civil Service Employees Association who joined AFSCME in the ad campaign said, "we hope to focus public attention on the impact these cuts will have so [Quinn] can influence his Republican leaders in Congress to do the right thing."<i>2</i>
<p>
When President Clinton came to Capitol Hill to celebrate the 30th anniversary of the passage of Medicare, the National Council of Senior Citizens ($71,516,000) played host and "provided goodie bags containing fans and hats with its logo."<i>3</i> <i> Newsday </i>said the event "amounted to a campaign rally" that was part of an effort to "argue that [Republicans] can't be trusted to preserve [Medicare]."<i>4</i>
<p>
The NCSC and other federal grantees have also resorted to exaggerated direct-mail pieces to spur grassroots activity. The Council recently mailed 500,000 business cards that declared, "The Threat: Gingrich Urges Replacing Medicare."  It went on to say, "Save Medicare! Call Congress." Says spokes-man Patrick Burns, "This is less of a moneymaker.  We're doing this to get people to take action."<i>5</i>
<p>
These organizations have every right to articulate their views, but the American taxpayer should not be compelled to subsidize the efforts of these special-interest groups.
<p>
<a href="/heritage/staff/wittmann.htm">Marshall Wittmann</a> is a Senior Fellow in Congressional Affairs.<br>
Charles P. Griffin is 
Deputy House Liaison.
<p>
<i>
The Government Integrity Project examines the practice of permitting tax-exempt organizations that engage in political or legislative advocacy to receive funds from the federal government.</i>
<p>

<i>1</i> "Sweeney Team Pickets Kasich's Office in Columbus, Objects to House Budget," <i>Daily Labor Report</i>, July 24, 1995.
<br><i>2</i> Robert J. McCarthy, "Area Municipal Unions Target Quinn in TV Blitz Against Cuts in Health Care," <i>The Buffalo News</i>, July 7, 1995, p. 7A.
<br><i>3</i> Carol Stevens, "As Medicare Turns 30, Its Health is Still a Big Issue," <i>Detroit News</i>, July 27, 1995.
<br><i>4</i> Martin Kasindorf, "Democrats Blitz GOP Plans for Medicare Cuts," <i>Newsday</i>, July 26, 1995, p. A13.
<br><i>5</i> Ceci Connolly, "Medicare Warnings on the Way," <i>St. Petersburg Times</i>, July 3, 1995, p. 1A.
</h4><BR><HR WIDTH="30%"><BR><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER></body></html>




</DOC>
