<html>
<head>
<title>RNC Briefing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center><h2>RNC Monday Briefing</h2></center>
<hr>
Excerpts from the RNC Monday Briefing<p>
<b>FYI</b>
<p>
Keeping a Bold Agenda<P>
<i>The changes in Medicaid, Medicare and welfare must still clear several legislative hurdles, and President Clinton has threatened vetos if the measures reach him in forms he does not approve. But for those who doubted that the Republican sweep of 1994 would be mirrored in this year's legislative dramas, and there were many in Washington, this week has been a revelation.... The Democrats' anxiety is clearly linked to a belief repeately expressed during recent months by ranking senators and others: that the Republicans would quickly lose their boldness when 'it came to the crunch' of health care. But the Republican have not done so"<br></i>
-R.W. Apple, JR., <i>The New York Times</i>, 9/23/95<p>

In a Rut<p>
<i>"My party is making a big mistake. [W]ith Medicare facing a financial crisis, Democrats are playing politics instead of coming up with constructive solutions."<br></i>
-Former Rep. Tim Penny (D-MINN),<i>The Waskington Post</i>, 9/28/95<p>

<i>"[Republicans] have taken a huge political risk just in calling for the [Medicare] cut they have. What the Democrats have done in turn is confirm the risk, The Republicans are going to take away your Medicare.  That's their only message. They have no plan. Mr. Gephardt says he can't pffer one because the Republicans would simply pocket the money to finance their tax cut. ...But that has nothing to do with Medicare. The Democrats have fabricated the Medicare-tax cut connection because it is useful politically. It allows them to attack and to duck responsibility, both at the same time. We think it's wrong."<br>
--The Washington Post, 9/25/95</i><p>

<i>"[The Republican medicare Preservation Act is] not nearly as Draconian as it was assumed by us Democrats. ...I'm not sure how many of us would be will to admit that."</i><br>
--Rep. Jim Moran (D-Va),<i> The Hill</i>, 9/27/95<p>

That Presidency Thing<br>
<i>"President Clinton tells White House reporters he has decided to impart the big picture to Americans. That's nice. Certainly every president should do that. ...Here all along we thought that as a result of studying at Georgetown, Yale and Oxford, and the years of governorship, presidential campaigning and occupying the White House, he understood long ago that telling Americans the big picture was an wssential part of his job."</i><br>
--A.M. Rosenthal,<i>The New York Times</i>, 9/26/95<p>

<i>"We gave up a long time ago on President Clinton as father figure. He is president as gifted teen-ager, elevating his undisciplined, incomplete, searching personality to a management style."</i><br>
--Columnist Maureen Dowd,<i>The New York Times</i>, 9/28/95<p>

</body>
</html>

