<HEAD><TITLE>Comments on Kirk's Works</TITLE></HEAD>
<body BACKGROUND="backgrnd.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff"  text ="#23238e" link="#3232cd"  vlink="000000">
<P>
<center><img alt="[ Return to Works List ]" align="middle" src="divide.gif"></center>
<br><p>
<center><H2><FONT SIZE = "+3">C</FONT>omments on <FONT SIZE = "+3">R</FONT>ussell <FONT SIZE = "+3">K</FONT>irk's <FONT SIZE = "+3">B</FONT>ooks</H2></center>
<center><img alt="[ Return to Works List ]" align="middle" src="divide.gif"></a></center>
<blockquote>
<A NAME="mind"></a><p>

<center>On <I>The Conservative Mind</I> </center>
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;The author of The Conservative Mind is as relentless as his enemies, Karl Marx and Harold Laski, considerably more temperate and scholarly, and in passages of this very readable book, brilliant and even eloquent.... It is history as well as argument. Familiar decades and political theories and controversies which usually, in our lifetime, have been illuminated by a searchlight from the left, are here revealed in unfamiliar highlights and shadows by Mr. Kirk's dexter beam."<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center>Gordon Keith Chalmers, in <I>The New York Times Book Review. </I></center> <P>
<center><a href="kirkwork.html"><img alt="[ Return to Works List ]" align="middle" src="divide.gif"><br><small>Back to Works </small></a></center>
<p>
<A NAME="burke"></a><p>

<center>On <I>Edmund Burke</I> </center>
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>
"Kirk's scholarship is wide-ranging--I do not in fact know of a contemporary writer who has his command of intellectual 'connection,' often exhibited in a passing allusion--of course he brings to bear his close knowledge of the vast array of modern Burke scholarship"
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<center>Jeffrey Hart, in <I>The National Review. </I> <P></center><BR>

<p>
<center><a href="kirkwork.html"><img alt="[ Return to Works List ]" align="middle" src="divide.gif"><br><small>Back to Works </small></a></center>
<A NAME="roots"></a><p>

<center>On <I>The Roots of American Order</I><P></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
"I cannot imagine how this essential task of referring back to the origins of order as it has existed in North America could have been more lucidly, unpretentiously, unpedantically, and yet informatively executed than by Professor Kirk. His book is exactly what people need to read, and he has made it easy, even pleasurable, for them to do so."
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<center>Malcom Muggeridge, in <I>Esquire. </I> <P><BR></center>


<center><a href="kirkwork.html"><img alt="[ Return to Works List ]" align="middle" src="divide.gif"><br><small>Back to Works </small></a></center>
<A NAME="eliot"> </a><p>

<center>On <I>Eliot and His Age</I></center>
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>
"In all the welter of boards and processed pulp cluttering the shops in any given year, there are pitifully few books; and of these, still fewer are informed with love and art in equal measure. Eighteen years in the making, Dr. Kirk's volume, to my knowledge the first such exhaustive examination of Eliot as a social and political eminence, is never unworthy of its subject."<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center>Charles Lam Markmann, in <I>The Nation. </I> <P><BR></center>


<center><a href="kirkwork.html"><img alt="[ Return to Works List ]" align="middle" src="divide.gif"><br><small>Back to Works </small></a></center>
<A NAME="john"> </a><p>

<center>On <I>John Randolph of Roanoke</I></center><P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
"The present gifted author finds a congenial task in presenting and analyzing a clear-cut body of political
thought that lay behind this extraordinary man, perhaps the most spectacular personality that ever sat in the Congress of the United States. And never has an historian done a better job of this kind. All the way along he throws light ahead, even to our day."
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<center>Samuel Flagg Bemis, in <I>The Yale Review. </I></center> <P>
<BR>


<center><a href="kirkwork.html"><img alt="[ Return to Works List ]" align="middle" src="divide.gif"><br><small>Back to Works </small></a></center>
<A NAME="enemy"></a><p>

<center>On <I>Enemies of the Permanent Things</I> </center>
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>
"Dr. Kirk is concerned with what makes civilization tick: its literature, its concept of morality, its politics, in short the norms of society, the 'permanent things' which we have been pretending do not exist."
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<center>Sheldon Smith, in <I>The Living Church. </I> <P></center><BR>

<p>
<center><a href="kirkwork.html"><img alt="[ Return to Works List ]" align="middle" src="divide.gif"><br><small>Back to Works </small></a></center>
<p>
<A NAME="professor"></a><p>

<center>On <I>The Intemperate Professor</I> </center>
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>
"Certain customary American verbal usages reveal discordered states of mind, and it is a pleasure to watch Dr. Kirk's ferocious attach on them."
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<center>Colin Clark, in <I>The London Tablet. </I> <P></center><BR>

<center><a href="kirkwork.html"><img alt="[ Return to Works List ]" align="middle" src="divide.gif"><br><small>Back to Works </small></a></center>
<p>

<A NAME="prospects"></a><p>

<center>On <I>Prospects for Conservatism</I> </center>
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>
"Conservatism at its best represents the best that is in a country.  Too often it has been equated with big business and the Coolidge reaction.  Mr. Kirk shows us how worthy is the tradition."
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<center>Francis Russell, in <I>The Christian Science Monitor. </I> <P></center><BR>
<center><a href="kirkwork.html"><img alt="[ Return to Works List ]" align="middle" src="divide.gif"><br><small>Back to Works </small></a></center>
<p>
<A NAME="portable"></a><p>

<center>On <I>The Portable Conservative Reader</I> </center>
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>
"It will help many Americans who call themselves conservatives to see the varied dimensions of that term, and to understand that much of what they do in their lives--as executives, say, or engineers--is socially destabilizing if not revolutionary in its implications.... Kirk has done an admirable job."
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<center>Andrew Hacker, in <I>Fortune. </I> <P></center><BR>
<p>
<center><a href="kirkwork.html"><img alt="[ Return to Works List ]" align="middle" src="divide.gif"><br><small>Back to Works </small></a></center>
<p>
<A NAME="mystical"></a><p>

<center>On Russell Kirk's mystical tales.</center>
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>
"Here and elsewhere, Mr. Kirk's wide erudition enriches the fruits of his imagination.... Try Mr. Kirk as fantasist. Unless you are allergic to the genre, you'll have a good time."
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<center>Edmund Fuller, in <I>The Wall Street Journal. </I> <P></center><BR>
<center><a href="kirkwork.html"><img alt="[ Return to Works List ]" align="middle" src="divide.gif"><br><small>Back to Works </small></a></center>
<P><BLOCKQUOTE>
"With patient, leisurely pacing and lapidary care, he builds his effects through layers of emotion and atmosphere ... until we are caught in a web of fascination and can be dazzled by a flash of fear. All these stories are excellent, and one, 'There's a Long, Long Trail a-Winding,' deservedly won a World Fantasy award"
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<center>in <I>Publishers Weekly. </I> <P></center><BR>
<center><a href="kirkwork.html"><img alt="[ Return to Works List ]" align="middle" src="divide.gif"><br><small>Back to Works </small></a></center>
<p><br>
<a href="kirkhome.html"><center><img alt="[ Image ]" src="kirkplat.gif"></center></a>
<p>
</blockquote>
</body>
