<head> 
<title>Chavez: Culture Fails a Child -- And A Teacher 
 -- 03/27/96 
</title> 
</head> 
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"> 
 
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a> 

<i>   March 21, 1996</i><br> 
 
 
 
<h2> 
Culture Fails A Child -- and A Teacher 
</h2> 
 
 
<a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html"> 
Linda Chavez 
</a> 
 
<P>   

BETHESDA, Md. -- She was a 45-year-old special education teacher, a   
wife and the mother of a 6-year-old boy. He was a troubled teen-ager   
who desperately wanted a gold Toyota Camry for his 17th birthday.   
Their paths crossed at a shopping center in Toms River, N.J., where   
the teacher drove her 1995 gold Camry to buy a sandwich on her way to   
a college exam.  
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
That chance encounter ended both their lives. The teacher was buried   
last week. The boy sits in jail, awaiting trial for murder and   
carjacking. As tragic as this incident was, it wouldn't have attracted   
much attention were it not for one difference. The teacher, Kathleen   
Weinstein, surreptitiously recorded the last half-hour of her life,   
which she spent counseling, cajoling and pleading with the teen-ager.   
The recording led police to the boy, Michael LaSane.  
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Unlike the 35,000 attempted or completed carjackings that take place   
each year, this one became a national story when bits of the   
transcript were printed in newspapers across the nation.  
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Most of the attention has focused on Weinstein, a remarkable woman   
right down to her last minutes on Earth. But it's her alleged   
assailant -- and the thousands like him -- we must begin to focus on.   
What is it that motivates a teen-ager to kill an innocent stranger?   
What can we do to prevent such horrors? Sure, we need tougher laws,   
more policemen and more prisons. But we also need to admit that   
something has gone very wrong with our culture when so many young   
people have no regard for human life and do not seem even to   
understand the difference between right and wrong.  
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Weinstein's alleged assailant doesn't quite fit our image of a killer.   
Yes, like 70% of young men who commit violent crimes, he comes from a   
single-parent household, and he lives in public housing, where crime   
is all too common. But his mother works in law enforcement, and his   
family is described by friends as God-fearing churchgoers. And while   
Michael had been in trouble with the police before, nothing about his   
record indicates he was capable of such cold-blooded violence.  
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
What is known about Michael is that he was obsessed with owning a   
shiny new car. He talked about it incessantly to his friends,   
describing how he was saving to buy his dream. It is a fantasy that   
consumes most teen-agers, reinforced dozens of times a day by TV ads   
that equate owning a new car with success, physical attractiveness and   
even intelligence.  
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
And it's not just cars; it's all manner of material things we're told   
we can't live without. The young are especially susceptible to such   
messages, particularly since so many young people have nothing -- no   
one -- countering such influences in their lives. Increasing numbers   
of fathers are missing altogether from their children's lives, and   
mothers are spending less and less time caring for their children.  
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
One-third of American children are now born to single mothers, and   
half of all children will spend part of their childhoods without   
fathers. About 70% of mothers of young children now work outside the   
home and often are so tired when they come home there's no energy left   
over to provide the consistent discipline and moral education children   
need.  
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Schools no longer teach right from wrong, either. For decades,   
intellectuals have claimed there are no absolutes - everything is   
relative, governed by the circumstances.  
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
In one young man's case, the situation was clear. He had to have a   
gold Camry. He bragged he was getting it for his birthday. In her last   
few minutes, Mrs. Weinstein couldn't teach lessons the whole culture   
had failed to teach this boy in a lifetime.  
<P><P> 
<HR> 
<P> 
 
<i> 
<center> 
Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br> 
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a>. 
 
</i> 
 
</blockquote></blockquote> 
 
 
 
