</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>When it Comse to Schoo, Mother Knows Best</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>When It Comes To School, Mother Knows Best </h2>
</center>
<hr>
<b>By Kathleen Howley</b>
<p>
I visited a friend recently, and was a bit surprised to see her nine- year-old son, Anthony, with his nose buried in a thick volume of Shakespeare's complete works.  
<p> 
"He's re-writing Hamlet in simpler language, and he's going to direct the play, with his sister and his cousins playing most of the parts," my friend explained.   
 <p>
Anthony looked up, for a moment, from his work.  
 <p>
"I'm going to be Hamlet," he said, with excitement.  
 <p>
But, of course. How silly of me to be even a bit surprised that a young boy's imagination would be captivated by the image of Hamlet -- the sword-wielding Prince of Denmark.  
 <p>
But, Shakespeare at nine? Or, even more astounding, a boy who voluntarily reads Shakespeare during his summer vacation?  
 <p>
My friend, who home schools both of her children, said Anthony was exposed to a bit of the classics as part of his English curriculum, and went galloping after the Bard on his own initiative during the school year.  
<p>
"It's nice that he has the freedom to really explore a subject that catches his interests," she said.  
 <p>
Other home schooling mothers have told me that their kids begin reading at an earlier age, and have a chance to learn in ways that fit their personalities. And, parents can choose a curriculum that gives their kids an education that emphasizes the basics, rather than the flavor-of-the-month approach to teaching.  
 <p>
Speaking as one who was interminably bored with the slow pace of the various public and Catholic schools I attended, I'm a bit jealous.  
 <p>
Home schooling is beginning to come of age. The U.S. Department of Education estimates that about 500,000 children -- more than one percent of all school-age children -- are schooled at home. Advocates place the figure at twice that. And, research shows that home schoolers are growing by as much as 40 percent a year -- fueled by the crumbing public school system, high tuition for private schools, and  
the increasing number of liberal Catholic schools that teach dissent to their young charges.  
<p>
Even the media is beginning to come around. Last October, Time Magazine ran a cover story that described the home schooling trend, albeit with a back-hand slap at Christians:  
<p>
"A movement once reserved largely for misanthropes, missionaries and religious fundamentalists now embraces such a range of families that it has become a mainstream alternative to regular public or private education," it stated.  
<p>
High profile examples, such as the Colfax family of Boonville, California, have helped to change the image of home schoolers. In 1987 Grant Colfax was accepted to Harvard University after being home schooled for his entire life. He graduated magna cum laude, became a Fulbright scholar, and graduated from Harvard Medical School. One-by-one, his home-schooled siblings followed in his footsteps to Harvard.   
 <p>
Advocates point to the fact that almost all of our early national leaders were home schooled. They'll tell you the kids get plenty of socialization, ranging from play groups where younger students mingle with other home-schooled children, to sports and theater groups for the older kids.  
<p>
What's more, in an age when family connections have never been weaker, they say that the one-on-one teaching inevitably strengthens the parent/child bond, and, as a result, imbues their kids with self-confidence and maturity.  
<p>
There is no doubt that home-schooled children have an academic  advantage over their group-schooled peers. In several studies over the last decade they score in the 65th to 80th percentile on standardized test. The national average is the 50th percentile.  
<p>
On the other hand, opponents such as the left-leaning National Education
Association, the union representing 2.2 million public school teachers, decry home schooling, saying it provides an "inadequate educational experience."  
<p>
In other words, no chance to tell the kids about condoms. No opportunity to show the students graphic pictures in their state-approved quest to promote sexual activity. No way to get the nihilistic message across that kids have no control over themselves.   
<p>
And, no opportunity to instill their version of values, meaning "yes" to recycling, and "no" to chastity, prudence, temperance, and faith.  
<p>
Do home-schooled kids miss out on something essential? Naw. I'd say it's the other way around.   
 <p>
It's the public school kids, who only get to be part of a family for the few hours between dinner and bedtime, who are missing out.  
<p>
Kathleen Howley is a syndicated columnist Copyright 1995, Living Word Syndicate  
<p>
Not for pub: P.O. Box 48, Cohasset MA 02025 * 617-383-0145
<p>
