<html>
<head>
<title>Chavez: Surprise: Punishment Actually Cuts Crime  -- 2/1/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<i>
February 1, 1996
</i>

<h2>
Surprise: Punishment Actually Cuts Crime 
</h2>
<p><br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">
Linda  Chavez 
</a>

<P>  
The murder rate is dropping dramatically in cities across the country, 
but analysts disagree why. In New York, the murder rate dropped by 32% 
last year; Washington, D.C., experienced a 10% decline for the second 
year in a row. The pattern is repeating itself in cities large and 
small, and murder isn't the only serious crime that's down. Of the 
Justice Department's index of serious crimes, only larceny theft was 
up slightly (3%) in the first six months of 1995. A new study by the 
National Center for Policy Analysis in Dallas suggests that putting 
more criminals behind bars at least partly explains why crime is 
finally going down - at least in Texas.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Overall, crime in Texas is now at its lowest point since 1973, and the 
murder rate is lower than at any time since 1966. Crime is falling 
most in big cities:  down 35% in Dallas and 29% in Houston between 
1991 and 1994, and the decline is  even greater for murder and motor 
vehicle theft - crimes that are almost always  reported and therefore 
most statistically reliable.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The precipitous drop is no great mystery to Morgan O. Reynolds, author 
of the study and a Texas A&M professor of economics. "Punishment 
works. Incarceration works. It's that simple," he says. Reynolds 
points to a "prison-building binge"  that tripled the state's capacity 
over five years. Texas now has more prisoners  per capita than any 
state in the country. And while many liberals would rate this a 
dubious distinction, more prisoners means fewer criminals out 
terrorizing their fellow citizens. Reynolds estimates that the lower 
crime rate means 1,140  fewer Texans will be murdered this year than 
in 1991 and 450,000 fewer crimes committed against persons and 
property.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The major problem in the exploding violent crime rate in recent years 
has been the inability of law enforcement to ensure that convicted 
criminals remain behind bars for a significant length of time. Prison 
became a revolving door through which violent felons passed repeatedly 
in and out, with stays so short it sometimes seemed convicts were 
being given a respite from their life on the streets rather than 
punishment. Parole was used by many prison officials throughout the 
country as a means to reduce prison overcrowding, not because 
convicts' crimes or their behavior in prison justified early release.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Texas was no exception. In 1990, Texas prison officials approved 79% 
of all prisoners considered for parole, in large part because of a 
federal court order  to reduce crowding in state prisons (a fate 
shared by more than 40 other states). With a threefold increase in 
prison cells since then, however, Texas' parole approval rate fell to 
22% in 1994. And there is good reason to believe that longer prison 
terms reduce crime, not only by removing perpetrators temporarily from 
society but also by deterring others who are considering committing 
crimes.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
As Reynolds notes, committing a crime is often a rational decision. 
Arrest rates are down in Texas, as in most other states, over the past 
three decades. The probability of being arrested for committing murder 
is down 21%, and down 22% for committing rape. With little chance of 
getting caught, criminals find the benefits of crime outweigh the 
costs, he says. Nonetheless, this calculus changes if the punishment 
increases dramatically - as it has in Texas. Expected prison time for 
convicted murderers is up 274% over the past three years, and up 152% 
for rape and 246% for aggravated assault.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Perhaps the most effective way to prevent crime is to make the 
punishment so  harsh and so certain that would-be criminals decide the 
risk isn't worth taking. Let the experts argue - Texas legislated 
those policies, and crime fell. 



<P><P>
<HR>


</blockquote></blockquote>

<center>
<i>Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br>
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a></i>.


<P> <br><center>
