<html>
<head>
<title>Chavez: Castro Acts, Clinton Crumbles  -- 2/29/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<i>
February 29, 1996
</i>

<h2>
Castro Acts, Clinton Crumbles  
</h2>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">
Linda Chavez
</a>

<P>
President should call for full sanctions and threaten a military 
blockade and retaliatory strikes if necessary.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
President Clinton faces a touch test of his foreign policy as he 
fashions a response to the downing Saturday of two U.S. civilian 
aircraft in international waters near Cuba. And, so far, he's in 
danger of flunking.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
When Haitian or Bosnian lives were at stake over the past three years, 
Clinton didn't hesitate to threaten and ultimately to use force, 
sending thousands of troops to defend dubious U.S. interests. But the 
brutal attack on unarmed Americans (three of four fliers were U.S. 
citizens) last weekend elicited no such reolve.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The best the president could muster in the hours after the attack was 
to send the Coast Guard to try to recover the bodies. And his 
announcement Monday that he would reinstate a ban on charter flights 
to Cuba doesn't go nearly far enough.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The administration's policy toward Cuba has been muddled from the 
beginning.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The president would clearly like to normalize relations with Cuba and 
has been steadily moving in that direction since he took office. But 
Fidel Castro keeps throwing monkey wrenches in the deal. The attack on 
two U.S. planes is only the most recent - and most surprising - of his 
actions.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Castro consistently has thumbed his nose at Clinton. In August 1994, 
Castro embarrassed the United States by allowing 30,000 Cubans to flee 
the island on rickety boats headed for the U.S. The president handled 
the crisis by detaining most of the refugees in camps outside the U.S. 
and repatriating those who would agree to return to Cuba. To do so, 
the president had to reverse the U.S. policy granting Cuban refugees 
automatic asylum that had been on the books for 30 years.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Last fall, in the hopes of improved relations with Cuba, the 
administration lifted some restrictions on air flights and on goods 
and dollars that could be sent to the island by Americans. And, for 
the time being, money from relatives will continue to flow.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Most observers believed that the administration was moving toward 
lifting the 34-year-old U.S. embargo against Cuba and would - in a 
second term - grant formal recognition to Cuba, which the United 
States has withheld for more than 35 years.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
But Castro has rewarded the Clinton administration's overtures with 
increased belligerence.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Castro continues to rule Cuba with an iron fist, tolerating no open 
dissent and inflicting terrible deprivation on his own citizens in 
order to maintain a powerful military, even as the economy of the 
island crumbles. In recent weeks, he has resorted to rounding up 
dissidents and human rights activists.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
In the past two weeks alone, Cuban state secret police have arrested, 
detained or searched the homes of 50 dissidents.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Perhaps the downing of the two U.S. civilian planes will finally 
convince the president that he's headed down the wrong path.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Castro understands only one thing: power. Castro will escalate his 
violence if he thinks he can literally get away with murder, including 
killing Americans.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The administration ought to use this incident to totally revise its 
Cuba policy.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Sanctions against Cuba ought to be fully reinstated and vigorously 
enforced. The president should warn Cuba in no uncertain terms that 
any repeat of the refugee blackmail Castro initiated in 1994 and 1980 
(when more than 100,000 Cuban refugees fled by boat to the U.S.) will 
be met with a military blockade. And any further military attacks on 
Americans will be dealt with in kind by retaliatory strikes by U.S. 
forces.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The president shouldn't expect much support from the international 
community on such a  course of action. It took hours of debate to get 
even a mild U.N. Security Council statement deploring Cuba's attack on 
the two planes. But Cuba is in America's back yard and Fidel Castro 
remains a threat, not only to his own people but also to ours. The 
next time Clinton thinks about deploying U.S. troops, maybe he should 
consider defending U.S. interests a little closer to home.

<P><P>

<i>
<center>
Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br>
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a>.

</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




