HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 09-Jan-97 13:54:12 GMT
Last-modified: Monday, 03-Jun-96 21:04:26 GMT
Content-length: 4637
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Chavez: Call it A Miracle -- 12/21/95
</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>


<center><i>December 21, 1995</i>
<hr>
<h2>Call it A Miracle </h2> 
<P>by <a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">Linda Chavez</a></center>
<p><hr><P> 

Call it a miracle - or perhaps just the triumph of tolerance and 
common sense - but there seems to be far less controversy over 
religious displays on public property this holiday season than in 
recent years. Both creches and menorahs are on display - albeit with 
some restrictions - despite the hostility of the ACLU and other groups 
opposed to such exhibits. 
 <P>
In a computer database search of newspaper articles from around the 
country, I found only 59 stories appearing since Dec. 1 that even 
mentioned Nativity displays, and most of these were announcements of 
holiday celebrations and events. 
 <P>
Admittedly, the ACLU did try to silence "Silent Night" and recordings 
of other Christian hymns piped into a government building in Chicago 
this year. But a federal court decided last week that the group was 
off base (as usual) in claiming  a few carols played over a 
government-owned loudspeaker system were an "establishment of 
religion" forbidden by the First Amendment. 
 <P>
Since 1984, when the Supreme Court handed down its first decision 
involving the display of religious symbols on public property, cities 
and towns have been debating just how far they can go in allowing 
Nativity scenes, menorahs, crosses and other symbols depicting 
important religious events. The court's rules - which seem to change 
each season - now permit religious symbols as part of state-sponsored 
displays so long as secular symbols are also included. And last June, 
the court expanded its interpretation, in effect saying jurisdictions 
couldn't interfere with the right of religious groups to put up 
whatever symbols they chose if the jurisdiction gave non-religious 
groups the right to erect secular, political or other non-religious 
displays on public property. Cities and towns now have the choice of 
saying no to everyone or no one. 
 <P>
Sometimes it's hard to remember that the holidays weren't always so 
complicated. Like most Americans over 40, I can remember when religion 
was at the heart of civic celebrations during Christmas. Denver, where 
I grew up, was well known for its wonderful public and private 
Christmas displays. My father always arranged a special family outing 
for the occasion. He piled everyone into the car for an excursion that 
took us throughout the city. First, we headed downtown to 16th Street, 
where the streets and stores were decked out in ornaments and tinsel, 
then to the Civic Center, where the exhibit proclaiming "Joy to the 
World" and "Peace on Earth" lit up the December sky and filled the air 
with music. We usually ended our tour in the east Denver neighborhoods 
best known for their elaborately decorated homes, many with mangers 
and Wise Men adorning the front lawns. 
 <P>
It was on this part of the trip that I first learned about Hanukkah. 
Through some windows, I could see what appeared to be candelabra with 
only a few candles asymmetrically lit. I thought perhaps they were 
special Christmas lights, like the "luminarias" that decorated my 
native New Mexico. But my father explained to me that these were 
Jewish homes celebrating a different holiday altogether - Hanukkah. 
Later I learned that the holiday commemorates the rededication of the 
Temple in Jerusalem in 165 B.C. after the Maccabees' victory over the 
Syrians. 
 <P>
Today children in many cities can learn about the Hanukkah traditions 
in public displays. Members of the Lubavitch community of Hasidic Jews 
erect large outdoor menorahs in parks and other public places across 
the country. 
 <P>
Americans are among the most religious people in the world. The 
radical separationists - who believe the First Amendment requires that 
religion be driven from civic life - are fighting a losing battle. 
America was founded on the freedom of, not from, religion. And there 
is no better way to celebrate that freedom than to welcome all 
religions back into the public square this holiday season. 
<P>
<center><hr width="50%"><P>



<i>Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br>
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a></i>.
<p>
