<html><head><title>Chavez: Children Do Suffer Most From a Divorce - 1/25/96
</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>



<Blockquote><Blockquote>
<i>January 25, 1996</i>
<h2>Children Do Suffer Most From a Divorce </h2> 
<P> <a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">Linda Chavez</a>
<br><p> 


As unusual as Michael Jackson's marriage to Lisa Marie Presley seemed 
in 1994, their impending divorce, announced last week, is all too 
commonplace. The superstar duo have become just one more statistic 
among the 1.2 million American couples who divorce each year.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With no little Jacksons to suffer the consequence of their breakup and 
a prenuptual agreement to protect each party's property, the couple's 
split is hardly cause for any public concern.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, the same can't be said for the approximately 700,000 
marriages involving children that dissolve every year.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These divorces are more than personal tragedies. They are a social 
problem with significant societal costs.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More than one in two marriages in the United States now end in divorce 
- the highest rate in the world. And a majority of these divorces - 
about 60% - are among couples with children.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For years while the divorce rate was skyrocketing, social scientists 
argued that children were largely unaffected by divorce.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many even argued that children were better off being raised by a 
single parent than they were watching parents quarrel or remain in a 
loveless marriage.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But evidence to the contrary has mounted over the past two decades. 
Now there is little doubt - based on overwhelming research results - 
that, on average, children of divorce are worse off than those who 
grow up in intact families.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Children of divorce are more likely to be truant, to do poorly in 
school and to get in trouble with the law than children who grow up 
with both parents.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The "California Children of Divorce Study," one of the most 
comprehensive of its kind to date, found that more than a third of 
children from divorced families experienced moderate or severe 
depression even five years after divorce.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Among adolescent women in the study, "almost all confronted issues of 
love, commitment, and marriage with anxiety, sometimes with very great 
concern about betrayal, abandonment, and not being loved," according 
to Judith Wallerstein, who analyzed the results of the study in her 
book Second Chances: Men, Women, and Children a Decade After Divorce.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many of these young women, she reports, resorted to short-term sexual 
relationships in response to their fears and anxieties.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Barring physical or severe mental abuse, it is nearly always better 
for children in a family if their parents stay together.  

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until relatively recently, parents understood this and considered it 
an obligation on their part to remain together - at least until their 
children were grown.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1960, 91% of children lived with two parents. No more. A whole 
ethos of self-fulfillment and personal happiness has replaced the 
ethic of self-sacrifice and concern for the best interests of one's 
children.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Too many divorcing parents put their own desires and needs ahead of 
their children's and then rationalize their actions by claiming their 
children will be better off if their parents are happy.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For once it would be refreshing if those who do selfish things would 
simply own up to their behavior.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Marriage is never an easy proposition. I have never known a successful 
marriage that did not, at some point, experience severe stress that 
could tear the marriage apart if the parties allowed it.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The difference between couples who remain married and those who 
divorce is not more love or fewer difficulties, but greater 
commitment.  

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Those who stay married often face identical problems with those who 
split up, but the former ride out the difficulties.

In many countries, divorce laws encourage couples in this process by 
placing lengthy waiting periods before a marriage can be dissolved 
unless special grounds exist, such as adultery or abuse.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most nations in western Europe, including most of the socially liberal 
countries in Scandinavia, require a minimum of a one-year wait before 
uncontested divorces are granted.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A number of states are considering stricter divorce legislation this 
year, including Iowa and Michigan.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After years of ignoring the devastating impact divorce has on 
children, it's time public policy took account of what's good for 
children, not just what's convenient for their parents.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Divorce still hitting a million kids every year Divorces affect fewer 
children now than in 1980, but far more than in 1970:  <p>


<Center><B>
Number of children whose parents get divorced each year<br>
 (in millions)</B></center>  
<p>
 <pre>
		1970   	.87<br>
		1975  	1.12<br>
		1980  	1.17<br>
		1985  	1.09<br>
		1990  	1.08<br>
</pre>

<P>
<center>



<i>Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br>
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a></i>.<p><center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
