<html>
<head>
<title>Chavez: Welfare Reform: Bill, Shame On You  -- 3/21/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<i>
March 21, 1996
</i>

<h2>
Welfare Reform: Bill, Shame On You 
</h2>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">
Linda Chavez
</a>
<p>
<i>Political ad promoting president as great reformer is just a fraud. </i>
<P>
BETHESDA, Md. -- The biggest case of welfare fraud in U.S. history is 
taking place right now -- and the perpetrator is Bill Clinton.

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Harsh words? Yes, but the president and the Democratic National 
Committee deserve it for the dishonest political commercials they're 
now airing trumpeting Bill Clinton as the Great Welfare Reformer.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The ads appear in 13 Midwestern and Western bellwether states where 
conservative Democrats traditionally determine presidential election 
outcomes. I saw them just last week in New Mexico, where they were 
showing several times a day.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
"Families destroyed. Children's dreams lost. The legacy of our present 
welfare system," intones the narrator over depressing pictures of 
poverty.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
"The president's plan: Increase child support enforcement, reduce teen 
pregnancy. Work requirements for welfare recipients, strict time 
limits on welfare benefits. Teach values in our schools. No work, no 
welfare -- rescue children from the destructive welfare system," 
bellows the unseen narrator as the pictures change.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
A worker punches a time clock, kids say the Pledge of Allegiance -- 
images of patriotism and bedrock family values flash across the 
screen.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
The ad ends with Clinton's last State of the Union address: "We can 
make real welfare reform a reality in the lives of the American 
people," he tells Congress.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
What the ad doesn't say is that Clinton has already vetoed two 
welfare-reform packages that would have accomplished everything the 
commercial claims the president wants.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
In December, Congress passed both a comprehensive welfare bill and an 
even more ambitious welfare-reform package in the budget 
reconciliation bill. The first would have saved more than $ 58 billion 
over seven years, the second more than $ 81.5 billion during the same 
period. The president vetoed both, even though he offered no serious 
alternative himself.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Among the bills' provisions were tough work requirements. Adults on 
welfare would have to begin working within two years and would face a 
five-year lifetime limit on their welfare benefits.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
In the area of child-support enforcement, the bills created a central 
registry to track deadbeat parents nationwide and required states to 
suspend driver's licenses for those who failed to pay support.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
To deter teen pregnancy, the bills allowed states to deny teen-agers 
welfare payments unless the young mothers agreed to supervised living 
arrangements.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The bills also did some things not mentioned in the Clinton ads.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The legislation proposed cutting off aid to drug users and alcoholics 
who now qualify for disability payments under the Supplemental 
Security Income program.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The bills also proposed limiting aid available to new immigrants, a 
provision that simply puts teeth in existing immigration law, which 
requires that sponsors of immigrants bear financial responsibility for 
their charges for the first five years they live in the U.S.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Americans want welfare reform, and Clinton knows it. In 1992, he 
managed to hoodwink a plurality of the electorate into thinking he 
would "end welfare as we know it." Clinton's use of the welfare issue 
was calculated to win back voters the Democratic Party has been losing 
to Republicans over the last two decades. The campaign successfully 
targeted key states with high percentages of "Reagan Democrats" and 
ran ads very similar to those the DNC is pushing this year.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
But the moment he was inaugurated, President Clinton quickly put 
welfare reform on the back burner while he attended to more pressing 
issues like gays in the military.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
It wasn't until 1994 that the president even bothered to send up a 
welfare-reform package.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
For Clinton now to try to regain the mantle of welfare reformer shows 
more than the usual political chutzpah. He's trying to defraud the 
American people in an election year.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
If the DNC's welfare-reform ad promoted a commercial product rather 
than the president of the United States, the Federal Trade Commission 
would yank it from the airwaves.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
At the very least, the ad ought to bear the warning: Voters beware. 

<P><P>

<i>
<center>
Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br>

<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a>.


</i>



</blockquote></blockquote>




<P> <br><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</a></center>
<P>
</body>
