<html>
<head>
<title>UN World Conference on Women</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<hr>
<center><h2>U.N. World Conference on Women</h2>
<p>
By<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/howley.html"> Kathleen Howley</a>
</center><hr>
<p>
<p>
Do you know the five genders? It's a widely-held tenet among 
radical feminists in America that there are at least five, if not 
more. And, they say, it's perfectly normal to flit between several of 
them during a course of a lifetime.
<p>
Typically, they are classified as: lesbian, male homosexual, 
transgender, and, for the less enlightened among us, male and female.
<p>
Geraldine Ferraro, the one-time Democratic vice-presidential 
candidate, is an ardent feminist and a radical pro-abort, yet she 
claims to have never heard about the new gender-speak -- despite the 
fact that it's standard fare in any run-of-the-mill college or 
university Women's Studies department.
<p>
Ferraro led the American delegation at the recent meeting to 
finalize the platform for the U.N.'s World Conference on Women in 
September -- where the definition of gender is guaranteed to be a 
ticking time bomb.
<p>
"I'm nearly 60 years old, and I don't know what the five genders 
are," said Ferraro, trying to deflect criticism about the feminist 
manipulation of the conference's lengthy draft statement.
<p>
In the official document, the word "gender" is mentioned more than 
200 times, often in a convoluted fashion, in sentences that beg for 
the use of the words "male and female." 
<p>
In fact, if you read the document, available on the Internet at 
the U.N. web site, it may raise the same suspicions that bothered 
delegates from Honduras, Guatemala and the Sudan. They were the first 
to object to the repetitive and somewhat odd use of the term, but 
later agreed to drop the issue until the main conference meets in 
Beijing.
<p>
You won't find the words "motherhood," "wife," or "family" 
mentioned in the official document, except for a handful of occasions, 
when they are referenced in a negative context as a means of 
oppressing women. 
<p>
Or, they've been put in brackets, which means that delegates 
objected to their use, and plan to remove them during the final 
revisions in Beijing.
<p>
The anti-fertility forces have had a spree during the drafting of 
the document. Abortion and the wide-spread use of dangerous chemical 
contraceptives, as well as sterilization, are held up, repeatedly, as 
among the most precious "rights" of women. 
<p>
Perhaps some day it will dawn on these meddlesome, middle-class, 
First World do-gooders that women from developing countries actually 
LIKE babies. I saw it with my own eyes, when I spent a year in West 
Africa.
<p>
They value new life. Not because it's another set of hands in the 
fields. But, because they believe that life is a precious gift -- and 
they don't have too many other bright spots in their difficult lives. 
<p>
I know such life-loving ideas are difficult for some First World 
brains to comprehend. We're always trying to think of new ways to 
relieve those poor women of the burden of motherhood. We, the minority 
of the world's population, believe that we know what's best for those 
underprivileged people who form the majority of the world's population 
-- in brief, we still believe in Colonialism.
<p>
But, they don't want our abortion clinics and our contraceptives. 
They want safe drinking water, simple drugs to help their children 
when they fall ill, and some economic opportunities for their 
families. 
<p>
And, there are many people in America who sympathize with them -- 
in fact, the majority. Sadly, the women from developing countries may 
never know this. 
<p>
Beverly LaHaye, president of Concerned Women for America, a 
conservative women's organization that is four times larger than the 
National Organization for Women, railed against the false image 
presented by the Clinton Administration's decision to send ultra-left 
Old Guard feminist extremists to Beijing..
<p>
"This conference is completely dominated by radical feminists. In 
the name of 'Equality, Development, and Peace,' this Beijing 
conference will be a taxpayer-funded promotion of abortion, 
lesbianism, and other left-wing crusades, such as disarmament, radical 
environmentalism, and socialism, that have nothing to do with helping 
women," she said.
<p>
We all know it's a travesty to hold a women's conference in a 
country that routinely practices forced abortions, mandatory 
sterilization of women, and female infanticide. It's a scandal to be 
the guest of a government that has a long record of imprisoning men 
and women in slave labor camps without trial, forcing them to make 
goods for export.
<p>
It's a joke to discuss the dignity of human beings in a country 
where possessing a Bible is a crime against the state, and where 
hundreds of Catholics priests have been imprisoned and tortured -- 
including three Catholic bishops who are still in prison, and three 
Catholic bishops who were tortured and beaten to death in 1991 and 
1992.
<p>
Yes, we know it's a travesty. But, the average woman in developing 
countries may not realize that the left-wing U.S. delegates do not 
speak for us. 
<p>
She'll be left to wonder about a world that sends her planeloads 
of contraceptives, but leaves her without access to simple anti-
malarial drugs.
<p>


 <i>Kathleen Howley is a syndicated columnist<br>
 Copyright 1995, Living Word Syndicate<br>
 Internet:73360.271@compuserve.com</i><p>
<center><br>

