<html>

<head>

<title>du Pont--  The Great Flat Tax Debate 
</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">



<center><i>December 6, 1995</i><hr>

<h2>The Great Flat Tax Debate 
</h2>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/dupont.html"><i>Pete du Pont</i> </a>
</center><hr>  
 <p>Should America replace its current income tax with a flat tax, a 
single, low-rate tax - say 19% - applied to ALL income above a 
personal exemption of, say, $36,000 for a family of four? 
 <P>
Yes, said the conservative team led by William F. Buckley, Jr. and 
former Democratic Governor Jerry Brown of California in a two-hour 
Firing Line debate taped at Texas Christian University.  Absolutely 
not, replied the liberals, captained by former U. S. Senator George 
McGovern and MIT economist Lester Thurow.  (Before reading on, you 
should know that I was a member of the conservative team.) The debate 
will be aired on PBS the week of December 18th. 
 <P>
The case for the flat tax is based upon three ideas:  it is fairer for 
all to pay the same rate; it will spur growth to create millions of 
jobs and billions of dollars in personal income, and the current 
income tax is grossly unfair, riddled with loopholes and preferences. 
 <P>
A flat tax will be fairer because everyone will pay it.  It will be 
progressive but not penalize effort, and all the special loopholes 
will be gone.  It will be simple enough for most people to fill out on 
a postcard. 
 <P>
As for growth, the National Center for Policy Analysis calculated that 
the flat tax proposed by Governor Brown in 1992 would create 2 million 
new jobs in two years and increase the Gross National Product by 10% 
by the year 2000. 
 <P>
Finally, few will disagree that our current tax system is 
fundamentally flawed and grossly unfair.  The government takes one-
third of what the average person earns each year (more if you are 
successful) and confiscates one-half of whatever is left when we die - 
the family farm, the small business we have built, or the savings we 
have worked so hard to accumulate. 
 <P>
Worse, the Congress opens and closes loopholes every year to reward 
its friends, punish its enemies, and, most important of all, to make 
sure its members are re-elected.  There have been 4,000 changes to the 
tax code since the last "reform" was enacted in 1986.  Our politicized 
tax code takes varying amounts of money from people who have earned 
it, and transfers it to people who haven't, but who the Congress 
thinks have a superior claim to it. 
<P> 
So who is for replacing this mess with a flat tax?  Well, the 
Washington Post:  "the ideal income tax is a flat percentage of all 
income above a threshold of $10,000."  President Clinton's chief of 
staff, Leon Panetta, introduced a flat tax bill as a member of 
Congress in 1982.  And 57% of the TCU students who expressed an 
opinion in a poll conducted prior to the debate favored a flat tax. 
 <P>
And who is against it?  Presumably Republican President Teddy 
Roosevelt, who helped enact the progressive income tax in 1913.  And 
Karl Marx, who initially popularized "a heavy graduated income tax" to 
redistribute income. 
 <P>
But most passionately, Lester Thurow, who confessed in a defining 
moment in the debate that if HE were writing the tax code it would 
contain a progressive consumption tax with top rates "way over 100%" 
so that the wealthy  would find it prohibitively expensive to buy the 
things they buy. "You couldn't have," he said, turning to Bill 
Buckley, "your boat."  
 <P>
Professor Thurow chose an interesting example, for the luxury tax on 
yachts - a mere 10%, not the 100%-plus he proposed - enacted by the 
liberals in 1990 to punish the rich nearly destroyed the U.S. boat-
building industry.  Those punished by the luxury tax (which also 
applied to aircraft and jewelry) turned out to be not the wealthy, but 
the thousands of working people thrown out of work and the taxpayers 
forced to pay $24 million in unemployment benefits to them.  And the 
luxury tax only collected $17 million.  So much for the Thurow theory 
of economics. 
 <P>
But the debate was more than sound and fury.  Senator McGovern came 
around to the view that the double taxation of company earnings was 
wrong.  And liberal economics writer Robert Kuttner conceded under 
fire that if a tax system raised the incomes of all but the wealthiest 
taxpayers 10%, and the wealthiest by 20%, it would still be a good 
thing.  Of course, he denied it could ever happen. 
 <P>
But no one on the left could satisfactorily answer Bill Buckley's 
opening question:  Why should a cab driver working 60 hours a week be 
punished for his extra effort by paying a higher tax rate than his 
neighbor who drove his hack only 40 hours?   
 <P>
Nor could they explain how the current tax system differed from what 
the American patriots listed in the Declaration of Independence as one 
of their grievances against the British King:   He has "sent hither 
swarms of officers to harass our people and eat out their substance." 
 <P>
That sounds an awful lot like the IRS. 
 <p>

<center>

****</center><p>

<i>The National Center for Policy Analysis is a public policy research institute
 founded in 1983 and internationally known for its studies on public policy issues.  
The NCPA is headquartered in Dallas, Texas, 

with an office in Washington, D.C.  </i><p><br>

<br>

