<html><head><title>25 Hours at Sea</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center>
<i>NEW YORK, NOVEMBER 17</i>
<hr>
<h2>25 Hours at Sea</h2><br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/buckley.html"><b><i>William F. Buckley Jr.</i></b></a><hr><br></center>

<P>
Countdown time. In little more than a week, the government of the 
United States is scheduled to close down, there having been an impasse 
between the Executive Branch of government and the Legislative Branch. 
An esteemed world leader is assassinated, resulting in an Air Force 
One flight to Israel. Lo and behold, in the very same airplane are: 
the leader of the Executive Branch and the two leaders of the 
Legislative Branch. 
<P>
They will be 25 hours in the same airplane! Could it be that the God 
Jehovah planned it that way? The golden opportunity to come together, 
35,000 feet up in the air, a thousand miles away from the nearest air 
field, and spend some time discussing the future of the Republic? 
<P>
But protocol reigns, and the airplane belongs, so to speak, to the 
leader of the Executive Branch; the two leaders of the Legislature are 
on board as guests. The initiative, therefore, has to come from the 
host.
<P>
But he doesn't approach them. Why? Well, we are told, he was grieving 
the loss of the slain world leader. The President of the United States 
could not drive from his mind his concern for intra-Israeli 
reconciliation. During the 12 hours heading east all he could think of 
was -- Hebron. To that problem, and the surrounding problem of the 
West Bank, he bent his mighty political powers -- that, and his 
concern for the grieving widow and children. 
<P>
On the journey back, the doctor told the President he simply had to 
make an effort -- as a sacrifice for his country -- to distract 
himself from his preoccupation with Israeli fratricide. He needed 
therapy. And, since Bill Clinton is a soldier, even if he never went 
through formal basic training, he consented to make the effort, but 
stipulated that the only game he would consent to play was Hearts, 
which reminded him of the valentines he used to exchange with the 
slain prime minister. 
<P>
Meanwhile, at the other end of the plane the two legislative leaders 
fidgeted, wondering when the President would come in, or else summon 
them to his quarters, to put it all out on the table. There isn't that 
much time left! is what was going through their minds. They looked out 
the window and saw Ireland go by, no summons. A couple of hours later 
they spotted Gander. Then Nova Scotia. Then Long Island. They 
permitted themselves to wonder whether a deal could be made between 
Long Island and Andrews Air Force Base, which after all was 90 minutes 
away, time enough to come up with something that would put off the 
crisis for a couple of weeks, maybe. 
<P>
At that point Senator Dole is said to have turned to Newt and 
suggested that maybe the President could be persuaded to meet with 
them in Dayton to discuss the problem. But Newt was getting a little 
fed up and said there wouldn't be any rooms available in Dayton, not 
till all those Serbs and Croats and Muslims were out of there. Dole 
nodded and was about to suggest an alternative meeting place when an 
aide appeared, with the landing instructions. 
<P>
They couldn't believe it! It was stipulated that the two leaders of 
the Legislature should disembark from the rear of the airplane. At 
first they reasoned that the purpose for this was to avoid any body 
contact with the President that might result in impetuous bargaining 
over what to do about the close of government at midnight. But no, Bob 
Dole said, there's no realistic fear of that happening, since there 
will be too much hustle and bustle getting out of the plane. There has 
to be some other motive. After all, in Israel we all disembarked up 
front. To change that plan now suggests a motive. 
<P>
Newt looked up. He had got the idea! He was a historian, he told Bob, 
and he knew something about affronts on a major scale, and this was 
one of them. It hasn't absolutely been established, but there are 
revisionists out there who are convinced that Brutus acted as he did 
because of the inferior box Julius Caesar had stuck him in at the 
Colosseum's opening on the Ides of February. The President, he said, 
is trying to provoke us! He doesn't want reconciliation, he wants a 
public shoot-out with as many blasts on TV as he can get out of it! 
<P>
Senator Dole furrowed his brow. There was always an alternative, he 
said. We could let the budget stay unbalanced? 
<P>
Newt shook his head. No. We'll follow the lead of Caesar, and see what 
happens.
<p>

<br><center>

[<a href ="/townhall/columnists/welcome.html.cgi"> Columnists </a>]

<br>[<a href ="/nationalreview/welcome.html"> National Review </a>]

<br>
