<head>
<title>Say Hello To Senator Lugar</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<i>NEW YORK, SEPTEMBER 15</i>
<hr>
<h2>Say Hello To Senator Lugar</h2><br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/buckley.html"><b><i>William F. Buckley Jr.</i></b></a><hr><br></center>
 
Richard Lugar was in town, and when that happens these days to the 
restrained, brainy senior senator from Indiana it means he is engaged 
in promoting his presidential candidacy. You shut your eyes, think for 
a minute: Who is Richard Lugar? The snippets form up deep in the 
memory. Yes . . . Rhodes scholar . . . mayor of Indianapolis . . . 
U.S. senator . . . strangely overlooked by George Bush when he went to 
the other senator from Indiana, Mr. Quayle, as Vice President, given 
that Lugar had been around longer and has here and there been 
prominent in foreign-affairs analysis.<p>

"I know more about foreign policy than anyone running for President or 
serving as President," he says, "and that is a modest claim." He is 
not the wisecracking kind, but it is an effective line and, one 
supposes, will be used by him in Iowa and New Hampshire, provided he 
can find an audience there that is interested in foreign policy.<p>

Well, what are his audiences interested in hearing about? The answer 
is: mostly taxes. Senator Lugar has proposed the elimination of the 
Internal Revenue Service. The what? someone in the company asked. Yes 
. . . exactly that. And a 50 per cent reduction in the capital-gains 
tax. And a $500 tax credit, not exemption, for every child.<p>

Well, but how are we going to finance all that?<p>

A consumption tax. Richard Lugar is all for growth, but he doesn't 
count on it to guarantee the long-term growth of the American economy. 
What we do need to do is to disencumber the economy, which is groggy 
from taxation and regulation. But the future of the economy is the 
world market. Hundreds of millions of people who want, and will 
increasingly be able to pay for, American products.<p>

But doesn't that run into the burgeoning protectionist bloc? Yes, 
indeed it does, and Pat Buchanan is doing a very good job in stirring 
that up. "I had an exchange with Pat recently and I told him the 
United States was running a trade surplus with Europe." He was flatly 
unaware of this, and showed it.<p>

"Senator Gramm said recently," a guest said, "that as a sometime 
economics professor he is well equipped to challenge the high-tariff 
people, but that this can't be done in a two-minute give-and-take or 
over talk radio. Are you going to talk about 'comparative advantage' 
in a stump debate?"<p>

Well, said the senator, the answer to that question is: You have to do 
it. "Do you know something? It costs one thousand dollars less to 
assemble an automobile in Indiana than it does in Mexico. One thousand 
dollars, because our workers have the training, the capital plants, 
the education, the advantages of transportation. Windshield wipers for 
cars, manufactured in Canada, are moving to the U.S. -- because it's 
cheaper. But Pat has them cheering and hollering with arguments from 
another age."<p>

Is it true, as recently heard, that if GATT and NAFTA were up for 
ratification tomorrow in the Senate they wouldn't get through? Yes, 
the senator said, that is true, and true also that some of the young 
Republican congressmen are infected with the protectionist virus.<p>

The candidate went on to talk about the problems of the front-runner. 
A few months ago, he said, Mr. Dole was running ahead of Mr. Clinton 
in California. Now he is behind. It is entirely possible that in May 
the GOP will wake up to find that no one candidate has got a majority 
of the delegates. So what has been planned between May and August? The 
answer to that is: Nothing. Nothing has been planned between May and 
August. But during that time I could knit together my positions -- for 
lower taxes, and increased trade -- and take on Clinton after my 
nomination. "But you have to learn to put your message, like on 
tariffs, down in black and white, in large type."<p>

Well, one guest asked, why haven't you done that? Gotten a couple of 
ad people together and given them that assignment? The senator is not 
fast on the polemical draw. He might have said that there is no 
equivalent of E=mc2 for the tariff argument, but he let it go. "That's 
a good idea."<p>

Is Senator Lugar getting anywhere? The objective indices aren't 
pulling for him. His finances are strained, and he barely showed up in 
the Iowa skirmish two weeks ago. He leaves you with the comfortable 
feeling of having been in the company of a decent, well-educated man 
who was a groundbreaking mayor, and is a fine senator.<p>

<br>
[<a href ="/townhall/columnists/welcome.html.cgi"> Columnists </a>]
<br>[<a href ="/nationalreview/welcome.html"> National Review </a>]
<br>
<br>
