<html><head><title>Buckley:  Yitzhak Rabin, RIP</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<center>

<i>NEW YORK, NOVEMBER 7</i>

<hr>

<h2>Yitzhak Rabin, RIP</h2><br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/buckley.html"><b><i>William F. Buckley Jr.</i></b></a><hr><br></center>

Viewing the TV and reading the papers in the days after the 
assassination one got some idea of how Mr. Rabin operated. One 
reporter said that to see Mr. Rabin was as easy as calling him up and 
taking the ten-minute trip from the reporter's office to the office of 
the prime minister. Another spoke of his "thirty or forty" sessions 
with him over the years.
<p>
And then there were the eulogies. A retired professor who served many 
years on the college admissions committee spoke once of the skill 
developed after a few years in detecting letters of recommendation 
that are synthetic. Just so, listeners to eulogies develop after a 
while an ability to discriminate between the formalistic and the 
genuine. Many eloquent statements were made, some of them -- from men 
and women who had worked closely with Rabin -- heartfelt beyond any 
histrionic power to deceive. The tribute paid by Henry Kissinger is 
not easily forgotten.
<p>
Three days ago I'd have thought it singular to recall that twice Mr. 
Rabin was with me on Firing Line and that he had once come with a 
friend to lunch with my wife and me in Switzerland. To say this now, 
which is to confess to only three encounters with him over the years, 
suggests I was practically an exile, all but ignored by the great man, 
so profuse were his journalistic and social energies.
<p>
The various passions stirred by his death are by now familiar. We know 
that a cruel element of the tragedy was the background of the 
assassin: of all things, an Orthodox Jew, rising to kill the greatest 
living Jewish hero. There is the consternation having to do with the 
political legacy. Yes, Shimon Peres will pursue the same ends. But 
although it is acknowledged that the death of Mr. Rabin will renew the 
momentum of the peace movement, its longevity cannot be taken for 
granted. When Lincoln died (Ambassador Eagleburger likened the two 
events) the nation was for a period buoyed by the sentiments he 
expressed in his second inaugural address, but it was not long before 
Reconstruction became the ugly thing it was.
<p>
In the case of Israel, something needs to be done to restore the 
perspective of those who fought Rabin. It is difficult to believe that 
people who deem themselves Israeli patriots would as recently as a few 
weeks ago design an effigy of Rabin wearing swastikas. In New York 
City one young follower of the late Rabbi Meir Kahane declared on 
television that violence can be "bad" but it can also be "good." He 
had whatever reserve of good sense it took to decline to say that he 
was pleased that Rabin had been a target of "good" violence, but he 
left that impression, cultivating as he was the line that the return 
by Israel of parts of the West Bank was high treason.
<p>
Policy differences, then, can hardly be expected to disappear in 
tribute to one martyr. Mr. Benjamin Netanyahu was convincing in his 
disavowal of the killer-division of the Israelis who join him in 
opposing the policies of Rabin and Peres. But there are Jews who are 
models of civil rectitude who oppose those policies, and they will not 
be silenced by the silencing of Mr. Rabin, nor should they: the 
security of Israel is properly the paramount concern of the Israeli 
government.
<p>
It's not all that easy to communicate to others the meaning of the 
birth of the State of Israel. Jeffrey Hart, writing several years ago, 
put it, "Now I can understand why Israel in fact has become sacred. 
The history of the twentieth century is, to put it mildly, unique. The 
Holocaust is a sort of hole in the cosmos, a guarantor of the 
existence of evil. It is an equivalent for Jews of the Crucifixion. 
Israel then became the equivalent of the Redemption. This is true even 
for relatively secular Jews. Judaism has never successfully separated 
God and Tribe. The People itself is the God carrier. I think that from 
a full experience of the twentieth century I am willing to accept the 
sacredness of Israel as a religious fact."
<p>
That is the reason the death of Yitzhak Rabin was a transfiguring 
event. That he died, and how he died, and when he died, and for what 
he died. <p>

<br><center>

[<a href ="/townhall/columnists/welcome.html.cgi"> Columnists </a>]

<br>[<a href ="/nationalreview/welcome.html"> National Review </a>]

